{"title_page": "Battle of Bajaur", "text_new": "{{For|the 1519 battle|Battle of Bajaur (1519)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{infobox military conflict\n| conflict          = Battle of Bajaur (''Operation Sherdil'')\n| partof            = the [[Insurgency in Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]]\n| image             = \n| caption           = \n| date              = 7 August 2008 \u2013 28 February 2009<br>({{Age in months, weeks and days|year1=2008|month1=08|day1=07|year2=2009|month2=02|day2=28}})\n| place             = [[Bajaur]], [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa|Khyber-Pakhtunkhwa Province]], Pakistan\n| coordinates       = \n| map_type          = \n| latitude          = \n| longitude         = \n| map_size          = \n| map_caption       = \n| map_label         = \n| territory         = \n| result            = Pakistan \u2013 led victory\n| status            = \n| combatant1        = {{flagicon|Pakistan}} [[Pakistan]]\n----\n{{Army|PAK}}<br>{{air force|PAK}}\n| combatant2        = {{Flagicon image|Flag of Jihad.svg}} [[Tehrik-e-Taliban Pakistan|TTP]], <br> {{flagicon image|Flag of al-Qaeda.svg}} [[Al-Qaeda]]<br> [[TNSM]]\n| combatant3        = \n| commander1        = [[File:Flag of the Pakistani Army.svg|20px]] [[Major-General|MG]] [[Tariq Khan (general)|Tariq Khan]]<ref name=\"WSJ1\"/><br>\n[[File:Flag of the Pakistani Army.svg|20px]] [[Brigadier-General|B.Gen.]] [[Abid Mumtaz (brigadier)|Abid Mumtaz]]<ref name=\"WSJ1\"/><br>\n[[File:Flag of the Pakistani Army.svg|20px]] [[Brigadier-General|B.Gen.]] [[Zafar Ul Haq (brigadier)|Zafar ul haq]]\n\n[[File:Flag of the Pakistani Army.svg|20px]] [[Colonel|Col]] [[Nauman Saeed (colonel)|Nauman Saeed]]\n[[Lieutenant Colonel|Lt col]]  Asif Ghafoor\n| commander2        = {{Flagicon image|Flag of Jihad.svg}} [[Faqir Mohammed]]<br>{{flagicon image|Flag of al-Qaeda.svg}} [[Saeed al-Masri|Abu Saeed Al-Masri]]\n| commander3        = \n| units1            = [[Frontier Corps]]<br>[[26th Infantry Brigade]]\n| units2            = \n| units3            = \n| strength1         = 9,000\u201315,000<ref name=\"WSJ1\"/>\n| strength2         = ~4,000<ref name=\"WSJ1\"/>\n| strength3         = \n| casualties1       = 30 killed and 4 wounded<br/>{{small|(Pakistan army)}}\n| casualties2       = 1,500 killed and 2,000 wounded<br/>{{small|(Militants)}}\n| notes             = \n}}\n{{War in North-West Pakistan}}\nThe '''Battle of Bajaur''' ({{lang-en|'''Operation Lion Heart'''}}), also known as '''Operation Sherdil''', was a military campaign in the [[Bajaur]] region of [[Pakistan]]. It was conducted on August 7, 2008 by the [[Frontier Corps]] and Infantry Brigade of [[Pakistan army]]. The operation was primarily launched to end the political movement of the [[Taliban]]. Bajaur area was administered by [[Taliban]] until 2007, and it remained [[Al-Qaeda]]'s central [[command and control]] for carrying out activities in Northeast [[Afghanistan]] and [[Kunar province]].<ref name=\"LWJ\">{{cite web |url=http://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2008/08/pakistani_troops_ret.php |title=Pakistani troops retreat after Taliban onslaught in Bajaur |accessdate=9 October 2008 |last=Roggio |first=Bill |date=10 August 2008 |publisher=The Long War Journal| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080919182156/http://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2008/08/pakistani_troops_ret.php| archivedate= 19 September 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/07/14/world/asia/14afghan.html | work=The New York Times | title=9 Americans Die in Afghan Attack | first=Carlotta | last=Gall | date=14 July 2008 | accessdate=26 April 2010}}</ref> Recent reports indicate that ongoing conflict has newly displaced an estimate of 7,000 people between 3 and 4 March in Nurgal district.<ref name=\"ReliefWeb 2020\">{{cite web | title=Afghanistan: Update on the situation in Kunar Province - Flash Update (09 March 2020) | website=ReliefWeb | date=2020-03-09 | url=https://reliefweb.int/report/afghanistan/afghanistan-update-situation-kunar-province-flash-update-09-march-2020 | access-date=2020-03-10}}</ref>\n\n==Ambush in Bajaur==\nDuring the early days of August in 2008, a check-post was established by the Frontier Corps to seize control of the Afghan-Pakistan border crossing over [[Tehrik-e-Taliban]]. Check-post was constructed near the town of [[Loyesam]] which is 12&nbsp;km away from [[Khaar]].<ref>{{cite news |author=Khan, Hasbanullah (AFP) |title=Bajaur battle kills 10 troops, 25 militants |url=http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2008\\story_8-8-2008_pg1_12 |publisher=[[Daily Times (Pakistan)|Daily Times]] |date=8 August 2008 |accessdate=24 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081007065647/http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2008%5C08%5C08%5Cstory_8-8-2008_pg1_12 |archivedate=7 October 2008 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref name=\"wsws\">{{cite news |first= James |last= Cogan |title= Military offensive displaces 300,000 in north-west Pakistan |url= http://www.wsws.org/articles/2008/aug2008/paki-a23.shtml |publisher=[[World Socialist Web Site]] |date= 23 August 2008 |accessdate=24 August 2008 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080826035719/http://www.wsws.org/articles/2008/aug2008/paki-a23.shtml| archivedate= 26 August 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref> Loyesam (or Loisam) is a strategic position that controls passage into Afghanistan's [[Kunar province]]. The militant attacks caused heavy casualties to the Pakistani army. Eventually, the army was relocated to Khar town.<ref name=\"LWJ\"/><ref name=\"NYT1\">{{cite news | author=[[Jane Perlez]], [[Pir Zubair Shah]] | title=Taliban Force Pakistani Troops From Tribal Area |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/08/11/world/asia/11pstan.html?ref=asia |work=The New York Times |date=10 August 2008 |accessdate=10 August 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Khan |first=Habib |title=Pakistani forces bomb houses near Afghan border |url=http://ap.google.com/article/ALeqM5jIE0IUn4WIiaMBpjG8SI_6H5RXzgD92FIS881 |agency=Associated Press |date=10 August 2008 |accessdate=10 August 2008}}{{dead link|date=July 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nSeveral days later, the Frontier Corps began a large-scale offensive under the command of Major-General Tariq Khan, codenamed Operation Sherdil (Lion heart), intending to regain control of Bajaur from the Taliban.<ref name=\"SAIR\">{{Cite web |url=http://pakistani.io/speech-in-urdu |title=Speech in Urdu |access-date=18 August 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160820005003/http://pakistani.io/speech-in-urdu/ |archive-date=20 August 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> About 8,000 troops belonging to the FC and Army, backed by [[AH-1 Cobra|Cobra]] [[attack helicopter]]s and fighter jets were deployed that attacked Taliban hideouts. To support the Army, the [[Pakistan Air Force]] responded with aggressive air campaign. Pakistani military sources revealed that the army was surprised by the resistance of the insurgents. Taliban used advanced tactics to fight prepared defense system.<ref name=\"IHT1\"/>\n\nBy the end of the year, the Army claimed that it had killed more than 1,000 militants, including the foreign commander of Al Qaeda, an [[Egyptians|Egyptian]] called Abu Saeed Al-Masri.<ref name=\"AFP1\">{{cite news |title=Battle of Bajaur a crucial test for Pakistan |url=http://afp.google.com/article/ALeqM5gYOBrkmVlZxO4u67N9L7I_fkNcPQ |agency=AFP |date=27 September 2008 |accessdate=9 October 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121004123134/http://afp.google.com/article/ALeqM5gYOBrkmVlZxO4u67N9L7I_fkNcPQ |archive-date=4 October 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The Army suffered 20 casualties.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20081214/ap_on_re_as/as_pakistan_on_the_front_line |accessdate=14 December 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081215184348/http://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20081214/ap_on_re_as/as_pakistan_on_the_front_line |archivedate=15 December 2008 }}</ref> \nThe military encouraged local tribes to rebel against the Taliban by raising the ''lascars'' (tribal militias) to fight alongside the government forces. The [[Salarzai]] tribe reportedly counted 4,000 armed fighters, responded favorably to this initiative.<ref name=\"WSJ1\">{{cite news |first=Zahid |last=Hussain |title=Pakistan Turns to Tribal Militias |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB122270429796586073 |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=30 September 2008 |accessdate=7 October 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081004030709/http://online.wsj.com/article/SB122270429796586073.html |archivedate=4 October 2008 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> On 7 October, the Salarzai elders announced that they had cleared their tribal territory of militants, and requested the deployment of government troops to consolidate the gains they had made.<ref>{{cite news|first=Khan |last=Anwarullah |title=Bajaur areas cleared of militants, claim elders: Deployment of security men sought |url=http://www.dawn.com/2008/10/08/top5.htm |publisher=[[Dawn (newspaper)|Dawn]] |date=7 October 2008 |accessdate=9 October 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081012045408/http://www.dawn.com/2008/10/08/top5.htm |archivedate=12 October 2008 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nAccording to several sources, the 20 September [[Islamabad Marriott Hotel bombing]] might have occurred in retaliation for the military offensive in Bajaur.<ref name=\"IHT1\">{{cite news |first=Carlotta |last=Gall |authorlink=Carlotta Gall |author2=Khan, Ismail|title=Battle of Bajaur: A critical test for Pakistan's military|url=http://www.iht.com/articles/2008/09/23/asia/23assess.php|work=International Herald Tribune|date=22 September 2008|accessdate=9 October 2008| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080926070554/http://www.iht.com/articles/2008/09/23/asia/23assess.php| archivedate= 26 September 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 October, during a briefing to the [[Majlis-e-Shoora|Parliament]], the military announced that the operation killed 2,744 militants, including 321 foreigners, and caused 1,400 casualties to the militants.<ref>{{cite news |first=Masooda |last=Bano |title=Briefing parliament |url=http://thenews.jang.com.pk/daily_detail.asp?id=140151 |publisher=[[The News International]] |date=14 October 2008 |accessdate=14 October 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090617210532/http://thenews.jang.com.pk/daily_detail.asp?id=140151 |archive-date=17 June 2009 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> On 25 October, the Pakistan forces reportedly recaptured Taliban militants in Loi Sam village.<ref>http://ukpress.google.com/article/ALeqM5hZu3Qpjdvqh8valFIKmIDGT_F_dg {{dead link|date=July 2010}}</ref>About 500 militants were reportedly killed in the Bajaur area on October 25.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20081025/ap_on_re_as/as_pakistan |accessdate=25 October 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081028122340/http://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20081025/ap_on_re_as/as_pakistan |archivedate=28 October 2008| title=Pakistani troops capture militant stronghold }}</ref> By the end of 2008, security forces were stationed at Torghudai, Nawagai, Utmankhel, and Salarzai. By mid-2009, the security forces controlled the bulk of the Mamund and Chahrmang valleys as well. The last operation was launched in February 2010 with fresh reinforcements to mop up the last pockets of militants, including the notorious [[Damadola]] stronghold. Bajaur was ultimately declared clear in March 2010. When the operation was completed, a large number of militants surrendered before the army.\n\n== Strategic significance ==\n{{Update|type=section|date=March 2012}}\nThe opinion of military leaders in the early stages of the battle asserted that it was a decisive confrontation of Pakistan's war against the Taliban. Military officials allegedly said the conflict \"could decide the fate of other tribal areas\" with Bajaur possibly being the most crucial militant stronghold outside of Waziristan. \n\nThe influx of Taliban fighters from the Kunar province across the border of Afghanistan was viewed as a further sign that dictated the nature of the fight by diverting resources away from fighting with [[International Security Assistance Force]].<ref name=\"IHT1\"/>\n\n==Results==\nOn 28 February 2009,<ref>[http://www.rp.pl/artykul/68095,269743_Talibowie_stracili_prowincje_Badzur.html Talibowie strictly prowincj\u0119 Bad\u017cur] rp.pl</ref> the security forces defeated the Taliban and other Islamist militants in Bajaur, which was a strategically important region on the Afghan border. Major-General [[Tariq Khan (general)|Tariq Khan]], who was commanding the military operations in five of the seven agencies stated that the Army and the [[Frontier Corps]] killed most militants in Bajaur, the smallest of the agencies but a major infiltration route into Afghanistan, after a six-month long offensive. The Pakistan Army killed over 1,800 militants. However, the forces suffered 30 deaths and four casualties.\n\n==Leadership==\n\n===Maj Gen. Tariq Khan===\nGen. Tariq Khan served as the Inspector General of the Frontier Corps during Operation Sherdil. He is known as the architect of the Battle of Bajaur. He is primarily credited with transforming the Frontier Corps into a highly efficient and professional counter-terrorism force. He supervised all operations in Bajaur. His physical presence at the forward-most positions during critical stages of the battle was an inspiration for the junior leaders and a morale booster for the troops.<ref>[http://www.dawn.com/2008/10/26/top1.htmrp.pl Archive | Your Source of News on the World Wide Web]. Dawn.Com. Retrieved 19 October 2011.</ref>\n\n===Brig. Abid Mumtaz===\n[[Brigadier]] Abid Mumtaz served as the officer commanding of Operation Sherdil in Bajaur. A commander noted for leading his troops from the front. He emerged  an example of his dedication to service on 9 September 2008, when the leading forces under his command reached at [[Rashakai]] town. The militants disrupted the communication line at Nissarabad, and he chose to stay on the frontline. He personally led the frontline forces for 15 days and did not return to headquarters until communication line was restored. He was awarded{{when|date=March 2020}} for his gallant actions and is now serving as the Major General. Mumtaz also conducted Khyber 2 operation in Tirah Valley in 2015.\n\n===Brig. Zafar-Ul-Haq.===\nBrigadier Zafar-ul-Haq replaced Brig Abid Mumtaz on 24 February 2010. He launched several operations to completely wipe out the Taliban's presence in Bajaur and expanded the security forces in each area of Bajaur. Brigadier Zafar-Ul-Haq pushed the Taliban away from the local areas and has ensured safety for the local people.\n\n===Battalion Commanders===\nBattalion commanders who served in Operation Sherdil.\n# Lt Col Baloch & Lt Col Munawar\n# Lt Col Anjum Saleem, Lt Col Nadir Khan, Lt Col Rashid\n# Lt Col Asad, Lt Col Ali, Lt Col Amjad\n\nThe dedication of combatant commanders helped the Bajaul Valley to end the terrorism.{{citation needed|date=November 2012}}\n\n===Col. Nauman Saeed===\n[[Colonel]] Nauman Saeed served as the operation commandant in Bajaur, where he was posted in and was due to assume command on 14 August 2008. However, owing to extraordinary circumstances, he had to leave for Bajaur on 6 August 2008. Miscreants surrounded a party that was sent to establish a post in Loesam. Nauman led the link-up unit on August 8, 2008 after the previous day's failed link attempt.\n\nThe troops were ambushed at Tankhatta, where they retaliate and held their positions for over 8 hours against well-entrenched militants to facilitate previous filtration of the party besieged at Loesam.{{Citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nIn another incident, the convoy of [[Inspector General|Inspector-General]] [[Frontier Corps]] Major-General Tariq Khan was ambushed on 9 September 2009 at Nissarabad. Col. Nauman went back to the ambush site with a tank and a Quick Response Force to extricate the crew of a vehicle that was disabled by the militants fire. His tank received multiple hits by RPG-7s and his operator suffered a bullet injury. However, they extracted the stranded vehicle along with the soldiers. He was awarded by the government for his contribution to the operation.<ref>http://www.dawn.com/wps/wcm/connect/dawn-content-library/dawn/the-newspaper/national/military-awards-announced-589rp.pl</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n{{Tehrik}}\n\n{{coord missing|Khyber Pakhtunkhwa}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Battle Of Bajaur}}\n[[Category:2008 in Pakistan]]\n[[Category: Battles of the War in North-West Pakistan|Bajaur]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 2008]]\n[[Category: History of Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]]\n[[Category: Wars involving the Taliban]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the 1519 battle|Battle of Bajaur (1519)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{infobox military conflict\n| conflict          = Battle of Bajaur (''Operation Sherdil'')\n| partof            = the [[Insurgency in Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]]\n| image             = \n| caption           = \n| date              = 7 August 2008 \u2013 28 February 2009<br>({{Age in months, weeks and days|year1=2008|month1=08|day1=07|year2=2009|month2=02|day2=28}})\n| place             = [[Bajaur]], [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa|Khyber-Pakhtunkhwa Province]], Pakistan\n| coordinates       = \n| map_type          = \n| latitude          = \n| longitude         = \n| map_size          = \n| map_caption       = \n| map_label         = \n| territory         = \n| result            = Pakistan \u2013 led victory\n| status            = \n| combatant1        = {{flagicon|Pakistan}} [[Pakistan]]\n----\n{{Army|PAK}}<br>{{air force|PAK}}\n| combatant2        = {{Flagicon image|Flag of Jihad.svg}} [[Tehrik-e-Taliban Pakistan|TTP]], <br> {{flagicon image|Flag of al-Qaeda.svg}} [[Al-Qaeda]]<br> [[TNSM]]\n| combatant3        = \n| commander1        = [[File:Flag of the Pakistani Army.svg|20px]] [[Major-General|MG]] [[Tariq Khan (general)|Tariq Khan]]<ref name=\"WSJ1\"/><br>\n[[File:Flag of the Pakistani Army.svg|20px]] [[Brigadier-General|B.Gen.]] [[Abid Mumtaz (brigadier)|Abid Mumtaz]]<ref name=\"WSJ1\"/><br>\n[[File:Flag of the Pakistani Army.svg|20px]] [[Brigadier-General|B.Gen.]] [[Zafar Ul Haq (brigadier)|Zafar ul haq]]\n\n[[File:Flag of the Pakistani Army.svg|20px]] [[Colonel|Col]] [[Nauman Saeed (colonel)|Nauman Saeed]]\n[[File:Flag of the PakistanI Army.svg|20px]] [[Lieutenant Colonel|Lt col]] [[Asif Ghafoor (Major General)| Nauman Saeed]]\n| commander2        = {{Flagicon image|Flag of Jihad.svg}} [[Faqir Mohammed]]<br>{{flagicon image|Flag of al-Qaeda.svg}} [[Saeed al-Masri|Abu Saeed Al-Masri]]\n| commander3        = \n| units1            = [[Frontier Corps]]<br>[[26th Infantry Brigade]]\n| units2            = \n| units3            = \n| strength1         = 9,000\u201315,000<ref name=\"WSJ1\"/>\n| strength2         = ~4,000<ref name=\"WSJ1\"/>\n| strength3         = \n| casualties1       = 30 killed and 4 wounded<br/>{{small|(Pakistan army)}}\n| casualties2       = 1,500 killed and 2,000 wounded<br/>{{small|(Militants)}}\n| notes             = \n}}\n{{War in North-West Pakistan}}\nThe '''Battle of Bajaur''' ({{lang-en|'''Operation Lion Heart'''}}), also known as '''Operation Sherdil''', was a military campaign in the [[Bajaur]] region of [[Pakistan]]. It was conducted on August 7, 2008 by the [[Frontier Corps]] and Infantry Brigade of [[Pakistan army]]. The operation was primarily launched to end the political movement of the [[Taliban]]. Bajaur area was administered by [[Taliban]] until 2007, and it remained [[Al-Qaeda]]'s central [[command and control]] for carrying out activities in Northeast [[Afghanistan]] and [[Kunar province]].<ref name=\"LWJ\">{{cite web |url=http://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2008/08/pakistani_troops_ret.php |title=Pakistani troops retreat after Taliban onslaught in Bajaur |accessdate=9 October 2008 |last=Roggio |first=Bill |date=10 August 2008 |publisher=The Long War Journal| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080919182156/http://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2008/08/pakistani_troops_ret.php| archivedate= 19 September 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/07/14/world/asia/14afghan.html | work=The New York Times | title=9 Americans Die in Afghan Attack | first=Carlotta | last=Gall | date=14 July 2008 | accessdate=26 April 2010}}</ref> Recent reports indicate that ongoing conflict has newly displaced an estimate of 7,000 people between 3 and 4 March in Nurgal district.<ref name=\"ReliefWeb 2020\">{{cite web | title=Afghanistan: Update on the situation in Kunar Province - Flash Update (09 March 2020) | website=ReliefWeb | date=2020-03-09 | url=https://reliefweb.int/report/afghanistan/afghanistan-update-situation-kunar-province-flash-update-09-march-2020 | access-date=2020-03-10}}</ref>\n\n==Ambush in Bajaur==\nDuring the early days of August in 2008, a check-post was established by the Frontier Corps to seize control of the Afghan-Pakistan border crossing over [[Tehrik-e-Taliban]]. Check-post was constructed near the town of [[Loyesam]] which is 12&nbsp;km away from [[Khaar]].<ref>{{cite news |author=Khan, Hasbanullah (AFP) |title=Bajaur battle kills 10 troops, 25 militants |url=http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2008\\story_8-8-2008_pg1_12 |publisher=[[Daily Times (Pakistan)|Daily Times]] |date=8 August 2008 |accessdate=24 August 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081007065647/http://www.dailytimes.com.pk/default.asp?page=2008%5C08%5C08%5Cstory_8-8-2008_pg1_12 |archivedate=7 October 2008 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref name=\"wsws\">{{cite news |first= James |last= Cogan |title= Military offensive displaces 300,000 in north-west Pakistan |url= http://www.wsws.org/articles/2008/aug2008/paki-a23.shtml |publisher=[[World Socialist Web Site]] |date= 23 August 2008 |accessdate=24 August 2008 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080826035719/http://www.wsws.org/articles/2008/aug2008/paki-a23.shtml| archivedate= 26 August 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref> Loyesam (or Loisam) is a strategic position that controls passage into Afghanistan's [[Kunar province]]. The militant attacks caused heavy casualties to the Pakistani army. Eventually, the army was relocated to Khar town.<ref name=\"LWJ\"/><ref name=\"NYT1\">{{cite news | author=[[Jane Perlez]], [[Pir Zubair Shah]] | title=Taliban Force Pakistani Troops From Tribal Area |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/08/11/world/asia/11pstan.html?ref=asia |work=The New York Times |date=10 August 2008 |accessdate=10 August 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Khan |first=Habib |title=Pakistani forces bomb houses near Afghan border |url=http://ap.google.com/article/ALeqM5jIE0IUn4WIiaMBpjG8SI_6H5RXzgD92FIS881 |agency=Associated Press |date=10 August 2008 |accessdate=10 August 2008}}{{dead link|date=July 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nSeveral days later, the Frontier Corps began a large-scale offensive under the command of Major-General Tariq Khan, codenamed Operation Sherdil (Lion heart), intending to regain control of Bajaur from the Taliban.<ref name=\"SAIR\">{{Cite web |url=http://pakistani.io/speech-in-urdu |title=Speech in Urdu |access-date=18 August 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160820005003/http://pakistani.io/speech-in-urdu/ |archive-date=20 August 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> About 8,000 troops belonging to the FC and Army, backed by [[AH-1 Cobra|Cobra]] [[attack helicopter]]s and fighter jets were deployed that attacked Taliban hideouts. To support the Army, the [[Pakistan Air Force]] responded with aggressive air campaign. Pakistani military sources revealed that the army was surprised by the resistance of the insurgents. Taliban used advanced tactics to fight prepared defense system.<ref name=\"IHT1\"/>\n\nBy the end of the year, the Army claimed that it had killed more than 1,000 militants, including the foreign commander of Al Qaeda, an [[Egyptians|Egyptian]] called Abu Saeed Al-Masri.<ref name=\"AFP1\">{{cite news |title=Battle of Bajaur a crucial test for Pakistan |url=http://afp.google.com/article/ALeqM5gYOBrkmVlZxO4u67N9L7I_fkNcPQ |agency=AFP |date=27 September 2008 |accessdate=9 October 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121004123134/http://afp.google.com/article/ALeqM5gYOBrkmVlZxO4u67N9L7I_fkNcPQ |archive-date=4 October 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The Army suffered 20 casualties.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20081214/ap_on_re_as/as_pakistan_on_the_front_line |accessdate=14 December 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081215184348/http://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20081214/ap_on_re_as/as_pakistan_on_the_front_line |archivedate=15 December 2008 }}</ref> \nThe military encouraged local tribes to rebel against the Taliban by raising the ''lascars'' (tribal militias) to fight alongside the government forces. The [[Salarzai]] tribe reportedly counted 4,000 armed fighters, responded favorably to this initiative.<ref name=\"WSJ1\">{{cite news |first=Zahid |last=Hussain |title=Pakistan Turns to Tribal Militias |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB122270429796586073 |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=30 September 2008 |accessdate=7 October 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081004030709/http://online.wsj.com/article/SB122270429796586073.html |archivedate=4 October 2008 |url-status=live |df=dmy-all }}</ref> On 7 October, the Salarzai elders announced that they had cleared their tribal territory of militants, and requested the deployment of government troops to consolidate the gains they had made.<ref>{{cite news|first=Khan |last=Anwarullah |title=Bajaur areas cleared of militants, claim elders: Deployment of security men sought |url=http://www.dawn.com/2008/10/08/top5.htm |publisher=[[Dawn (newspaper)|Dawn]] |date=7 October 2008 |accessdate=9 October 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081012045408/http://www.dawn.com/2008/10/08/top5.htm |archivedate=12 October 2008 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nAccording to several sources, the 20 September [[Islamabad Marriott Hotel bombing]] might have occurred in retaliation for the military offensive in Bajaur.<ref name=\"IHT1\">{{cite news |first=Carlotta |last=Gall |authorlink=Carlotta Gall |author2=Khan, Ismail|title=Battle of Bajaur: A critical test for Pakistan's military|url=http://www.iht.com/articles/2008/09/23/asia/23assess.php|work=International Herald Tribune|date=22 September 2008|accessdate=9 October 2008| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080926070554/http://www.iht.com/articles/2008/09/23/asia/23assess.php| archivedate= 26 September 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 October, during a briefing to the [[Majlis-e-Shoora|Parliament]], the military announced that the operation killed 2,744 militants, including 321 foreigners, and caused 1,400 casualties to the militants.<ref>{{cite news |first=Masooda |last=Bano |title=Briefing parliament |url=http://thenews.jang.com.pk/daily_detail.asp?id=140151 |publisher=[[The News International]] |date=14 October 2008 |accessdate=14 October 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090617210532/http://thenews.jang.com.pk/daily_detail.asp?id=140151 |archive-date=17 June 2009 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> On 25 October, the Pakistan forces reportedly recaptured Taliban militants in Loi Sam village.<ref>http://ukpress.google.com/article/ALeqM5hZu3Qpjdvqh8valFIKmIDGT_F_dg {{dead link|date=July 2010}}</ref>About 500 militants were reportedly killed in the Bajaur area on October 25.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20081025/ap_on_re_as/as_pakistan |accessdate=25 October 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081028122340/http://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20081025/ap_on_re_as/as_pakistan |archivedate=28 October 2008| title=Pakistani troops capture militant stronghold }}</ref> By the end of 2008, security forces were stationed at Torghudai, Nawagai, Utmankhel, and Salarzai. By mid-2009, the security forces controlled the bulk of the Mamund and Chahrmang valleys as well. The last operation was launched in February 2010 with fresh reinforcements to mop up the last pockets of militants, including the notorious [[Damadola]] stronghold. Bajaur was ultimately declared clear in March 2010. When the operation was completed, a large number of militants surrendered before the army.\n\n== Strategic significance ==\n{{Update|type=section|date=March 2012}}\nThe opinion of military leaders in the early stages of the battle asserted that it was a decisive confrontation of Pakistan's war against the Taliban. Military officials allegedly said the conflict \"could decide the fate of other tribal areas\" with Bajaur possibly being the most crucial militant stronghold outside of Waziristan. \n\nThe influx of Taliban fighters from the Kunar province across the border of Afghanistan was viewed as a further sign that dictated the nature of the fight by diverting resources away from fighting with [[International Security Assistance Force]].<ref name=\"IHT1\"/>\n\n==Results==\nOn 28 February 2009,<ref>[http://www.rp.pl/artykul/68095,269743_Talibowie_stracili_prowincje_Badzur.html Talibowie strictly prowincj\u0119 Bad\u017cur] rp.pl</ref> the security forces defeated the Taliban and other Islamist militants in Bajaur, which was a strategically important region on the Afghan border. Major-General [[Tariq Khan (general)|Tariq Khan]], who was commanding the military operations in five of the seven agencies stated that the Army and the [[Frontier Corps]] killed most militants in Bajaur, the smallest of the agencies but a major infiltration route into Afghanistan, after a six-month long offensive. The Pakistan Army killed over 1,800 militants. However, the forces suffered 30 deaths and four casualties.\n\n==Leadership==\n\n===Maj Gen. Tariq Khan===\nGen. Tariq Khan served as the Inspector General of the Frontier Corps during Operation Sherdil. He is known as the architect of the Battle of Bajaur. He is primarily credited with transforming the Frontier Corps into a highly efficient and professional counter-terrorism force. He supervised all operations in Bajaur. His physical presence at the forward-most positions during critical stages of the battle was an inspiration for the junior leaders and a morale booster for the troops.<ref>[http://www.dawn.com/2008/10/26/top1.htmrp.pl Archive | Your Source of News on the World Wide Web]. Dawn.Com. Retrieved 19 October 2011.</ref>\n\n===Brig. Abid Mumtaz===\n[[Brigadier]] Abid Mumtaz served as the officer commanding of Operation Sherdil in Bajaur. A commander noted for leading his troops from the front. He emerged  an example of his dedication to service on 9 September 2008, when the leading forces under his command reached at [[Rashakai]] town. The militants disrupted the communication line at Nissarabad, and he chose to stay on the frontline. He personally led the frontline forces for 15 days and did not return to headquarters until communication line was restored. He was awarded{{when|date=March 2020}} for his gallant actions and is now serving as the Major General. Mumtaz also conducted Khyber 2 operation in Tirah Valley in 2015.\n\n===Brig. Zafar-Ul-Haq.===\nBrigadier Zafar-ul-Haq replaced Brig Abid Mumtaz on 24 February 2010. He launched several operations to completely wipe out the Taliban's presence in Bajaur and expanded the security forces in each area of Bajaur. Brigadier Zafar-Ul-Haq pushed the Taliban away from the local areas and has ensured safety for the local people.\n\n===Battalion Commanders===\nBattalion commanders who served in Operation Sherdil.\n# Lt Col Baloch & Lt Col Munawar\n# Lt Col Anjum Saleem, Lt Col Nadir Khan, Lt Col Rashid\n# Lt Col Asad, Lt Col Ali, Lt Col Amjad\n\nThe dedication of combatant commanders helped the Bajaul Valley to end the terrorism.{{citation needed|date=November 2012}}\n\n===Col. Nauman Saeed===\n[[Colonel]] Nauman Saeed served as the operation commandant in Bajaur, where he was posted in and was due to assume command on 14 August 2008. However, owing to extraordinary circumstances, he had to leave for Bajaur on 6 August 2008. Miscreants surrounded a party that was sent to establish a post in Loesam. Nauman led the link-up unit on August 8, 2008 after the previous day's failed link attempt.\n\nThe troops were ambushed at Tankhatta, where they retaliate and held their positions for over 8 hours against well-entrenched militants to facilitate previous filtration of the party besieged at Loesam.{{Citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nIn another incident, the convoy of [[Inspector General|Inspector-General]] [[Frontier Corps]] Major-General Tariq Khan was ambushed on 9 September 2009 at Nissarabad. Col. Nauman went back to the ambush site with a tank and a Quick Response Force to extricate the crew of a vehicle that was disabled by the militants fire. His tank received multiple hits by RPG-7s and his operator suffered a bullet injury. However, they extracted the stranded vehicle along with the soldiers. He was awarded by the government for his contribution to the operation.<ref>http://www.dawn.com/wps/wcm/connect/dawn-content-library/dawn/the-newspaper/national/military-awards-announced-589rp.pl</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n{{Tehrik}}\n\n{{coord missing|Khyber Pakhtunkhwa}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Battle Of Bajaur}}\n[[Category:2008 in Pakistan]]\n[[Category: Battles of the War in North-West Pakistan|Bajaur]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 2008]]\n[[Category: History of Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]]\n[[Category: Wars involving the Taliban]]\n", "name_user": "Hassam Farooq", "label": "safe", "comment": "Lt Colonel Asif ghafoor who is now major General in Pakistan army, served as DG ISPR now serving as GOC 40 division Okara, took part in this battle and fought war as soldier, proof for reference is present on YouTube \"Power play Arshad Sharif documentary on operation Sherdill,Ary News\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Bajaur"}
{"title_page": "Brenda Hale, Baroness Hale of Richmond", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = The Baroness Hale of Richmond\n| honorific-suffix = {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|DBE|PC|FBA}}\n| image = Baroness Hale of Richmond 2019.jpg\n| office = [[President of the Supreme Court of the United Kingdom]]\n| term_start = 5 September 2017\n| term_end = 11 January 2020\n| deputy = {{Unbulleted list |[[Jonathan Mance, Baron Mance|Lord Mance]] |[[Robert Reed, Lord Reed|Lord Reed]]}}\n| predecessor = [[David Neuberger, Baron Neuberger of Abbotsbury|Lord Neuberger]]\n| successor = [[Robert Reed, Lord Reed]]\n| office1 = [[Deputy President of the Supreme Court of the United Kingdom]]\n| term_start1 = 28 June 2013\n| term_end1 = 4 September 2017\n| monarch = [[Elizabeth II]]\n| predecessor1 = [[David Hope, Baron Hope of Craighead|Lord Hope]]\n| president1 = [[David Neuberger, Baron Neuberger of Abbotsbury|Lord Neuberger]]\n| successor1 = [[Jonathan Mance, Baron Mance|Lord Mance]]\n| office2 = [[Judges of the Supreme Court of the United Kingdom|Justice of the Supreme Court of the United Kingdom]]\n| term_start2 = 1 October 2009\n| term_end2 = 10 January 2020\n| predecessor2 = ''Position created''\n| successor2 = [[Nicholas Hamblen, Lord Hamblen]]\n| office3 = [[Lord of Appeal in Ordinary]]\n| term_start3 = 12 January 2004\n| term_end3 = 30 September 2009\n| predecessor3 = [[Peter Millett, Baron Millett|Lord Millett]]\n| successor3 = ''Position abolished''\n| office4 = [[Lady Justice of Appeal]]\n| term_start4 = 1999\n| term_end4 = 2003\n| office5 = [[High Court judge (England and Wales)|High Court Judge<br />Family Division]]\n| term_start5 = 1994\n| term_end5 = 1999\n| appointer5 = [[Elizabeth II]]\n| predecessor4 = \n| office6 = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br/><small>[[Lords Temporal|Lord Temporal (Judicial Peer)]]</small>\n| term_start6 = 12 January 2004\n| term_end6 = 1 October 2009\n| title7 = Chancellor of the [[University of Bristol]]\n| order7 = 7th\n| term_start7 = 2004\n| term_end7 = 2017\n| predecessor7 = Sir [[Jeremy Morse]]\n| successor7 = Sir [[Paul Nurse]]\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1945|01|31}}\n| birth_place = [[Leeds]], [[West Riding of Yorkshire]], England\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| restingplace = \n| birthname = Brenda Marjorie Hale\n| spouse = {{unbulleted list | {{marriage|Anthony Hoggett|1968|1992|end=div}} | {{marriage|Julian Farrand |1992}}}}\n| children = 1\n| residence = \n| alma_mater = [[Girton College, Cambridge]]\n| office8 = Non-Permanent Judge of the [[Court of Final Appeal (Hong Kong)|Court of Final Appeal]] of Hong Kong\n| term_start8 = 30 July 2018\n| term_end8 = \n}}\n\n'''Brenda Marjorie Hale, Baroness Hale of Richmond''', {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|DBE|PC|FBA|sep= }} (born 31 January 1945), known as '''Lady Hale''', is a British judge who served as [[President of the Supreme Court of the United Kingdom]] from 2017 to 2020, and serves as a member of the [[House of Lords]] as Lord Temporal.<ref>[http://www.judiciary.gov.uk/keyfacts/list_judiciary/senior_judiciary_list.htm Senior Judiciary List] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120618220245/http://www.judiciary.gov.uk/about-the-judiciary/judges-magistrates-and-tribunal-judges/list-of-members-of-the-judiciary/senior-judiciary-list |date=18 June 2012 }}, Ministry of Justice.</ref>\n\nIn 2004, she joined the [[House of Lords]] as a  [[Lord of Appeal in Ordinary]]. She is the only woman to have been appointed to that position. She served as a Law Lord until 2009 when she, along with the other Law Lords, transferred to the new [[Supreme Court of the United Kingdom|Supreme Court]] as a result of the [[Constitutional Reform Act 2005]]. She served as [[Deputy President of the Supreme Court of the United Kingdom|Deputy President of the Supreme Court]] from 2013 to 2017.\n\nOn 5 September 2017, Hale was appointed under the Premiership of [[Theresa May]] to serve as [[President of the Supreme Court of the United Kingdom|President of the Supreme Court]], and was sworn in on 2 October 2017. She is the third person and first woman to serve in the role. Hale is one of three women to have been appointed to the Supreme Court (alongside [[Jill Black, Lady Black of Derwent|Lady Black]] and [[Mary Arden, Lady Arden|Lady Arden]]).\n\nSince 30 July 2018, Hale has been a non-permanent judge of the [[Court of Final Appeal (Hong Kong)|Court of Final Appeal of Hong Kong]]. Hale has also been Honorary President of the [[Cambridge University Law Society]] since 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.law.cam.ac.uk/press/events/2016/01/culs-lecture-lady-hale-life-lady-law-lord|title=CULS Lecture: Lady Hale \u2013 'The Life of A Lady Law Lord'|website=[[Faculty of Law, University of Cambridge]]|date=3 February 2016|access-date=10 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180110174810/https://www.law.cam.ac.uk/press/events/2016/01/culs-lecture-lady-hale-life-lady-law-lord|archive-date=10 January 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn the 11th January 2020, Lady Hale was succeeded by Lord Reed as President of Supreme Court.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.legalcheek.com/2020/01/lord-reed-sworn-in-as-new-supreme-court-president/|title=Lord Reed sworn in as new Supreme Court president|date=2020-01-13|website=Legal Cheek|access-date=2020-01-13}}</ref> \n\n==Early life==\nBrenda Marjorie Hale<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.supremecourt.uk/about/biographies-of-the-justices.html|publisher=Supreme Court of the United Kingdom|accessdate=24 September 2019|title=Biographies of the Justices|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190522153902/https://www.supremecourt.uk/about/biographies-of-the-justices.html|archive-date=22 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> was born on 31 January 1945 in [[Leeds]], [[West Riding of Yorkshire]]. Both her parents were headteachers. She has two sisters. Hale lived in [[Redcar]] until the age of three when she moved with her parents to [[Richmond, North Yorkshire]]. She was educated at the Richmond High School for Girls (now part of [[Richmond School]]), where she and her two sisters were all [[head girl]]s.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Amos |first1=Mike |title=Judge not lest thou be judged, but the column\u2019s still much impressed by Lady Hale |url=https://www.theboltonnews.co.uk/news/16182345.amp/ |accessdate=27 December 2019 |work=[[Bolton News]] |date=5 April 2018}}</ref> She later studied at [[Girton College, Cambridge]] (the first from her school to attend Cambridge), where she read law. Hale was one of six women in her class, which had 110 men, and graduated with a [[British undergraduate degree classification#Variations of first-class honours|starred first]] and top of her class in 1966.<ref name=Guardian/><ref name=New/>\n\nAfter becoming an assistant law lecturer at the [[Victoria University of Manchester]] (now the [[University of Manchester]]), she was [[Call to the bar|called to the Bar]] by [[Gray's Inn]] in 1969, topping the list in the bar finals for that year.<ref name=Guardian>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2004/jan/09/lords.women|work=The Guardian|title=The Guardian profile: Lady Brenda Hale|last=Dyer|first=Clare|accessdate=24 September 2019|date=9 January 2004|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161202010338/https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2004/jan/09/lords.women|archive-date=2 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=New>{{cite news|last=Stokel-Walker|first=Chris|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/brexit/2019/09/lady-hale-gently-determined-president-supreme-court-overruled-boris-johnson|work=New Statesman|date=24 September 2019|accessdate=24 September 2019|title=Lady Hale, the gently determined president of the Supreme Court that overruled Boris Johnson}}</ref>\n\nWorking part-time as a [[barrister]], Hale spent 18 years mostly in academia, becoming Professor of Law at Manchester in 1986. Two years earlier, she became the first woman and youngest person to be appointed to the [[Law Commission (England and Wales)|Law Commission]], overseeing a number of important reforms<ref name=\"NYT 92419\">{{cite news |author1=Yonette Joseph |author2=Ceylan Yeginsu |title=Lady Hale, U.K. Supreme Court Judge, Speaks Calmly and Brings Down the Hammer |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/24/world/europe/lady-hale-supreme-court-uk.html |accessdate=September 24, 2019 |work=The New York Times |date=24 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190925082602/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/24/world/europe/lady-hale-supreme-court-uk.html |archive-date=25 September 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> in [[family law]] during her nine years with the Commission. In 1989, she was appointed [[Queen's Counsel]].<ref name=Guardian/>\n\n==Judicial career==\nHale was appointed a [[Recorder (judge)|Recorder]] (a part-time [[Circuit judge (UK)|circuit judge]]) in 1989, and in 1994 became a [[High Court judge (England and Wales)|judge]] in the Family Division of the [[High Court of Justice of England and Wales|High Court of Justice]] (styled The Honourable Mrs Justice Hale).<ref name=Guardian/> Upon her appointment, as is convention, she was appointed a [[Order of the British Empire|Dame Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] (DBE). In 1999, Hale followed [[Elizabeth Butler-Sloss, Baroness Butler-Sloss|Dame Elizabeth Butler-Sloss]] to become only the second woman to be appointed to the [[Court of Appeal of England and Wales|Court of Appeal]] (styled The Right Honourable Lady Justice Hale), entering the [[Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council|Privy Council]] at the same time.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/law/2017/jul/21/brenda-hale-to-become-supreme-courts-first-female-president-reports|work=The Guardian|title=Brenda Hale to become first female president of supreme court \u2013 reports|last=Slawson|first=Nicola|date=21 July 2017|accessdate=24 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181230180612/https://www.theguardian.com/law/2017/jul/21/brenda-hale-to-become-supreme-courts-first-female-president-reports|archive-date=30 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 January 2004, she was appointed the first female [[Lord of Appeal in Ordinary]] and was created a life peer as '''Baroness Hale of Richmond''', of Easby in the County of North Yorkshire,<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=57179 |page=503 |date=15 January 2004}}</ref> under the [[Appellate Jurisdiction Act 1876]].<ref name=Supreme/>\n\nIn June 2013, she was appointed [[Deputy President of the Supreme Court of the United Kingdom]] to succeed [[David Hope, Baron Hope of Craighead|Lord Hope of Craighead]].<ref name=Supreme>{{cite web|url=https://www.supremecourt.uk/news/lady-hale-to-be-next-deputy-president-of-supreme-court.html|title=Lady Hale to be next Deputy President of Supreme Court|publisher=Supreme Court of the United Kingdom|date=24 June 2013|accessdate=24 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140205090531/http://supremecourt.uk/news/lady-hale-to-be-next-deputy-president-of-supreme-court.html|archive-date=5 February 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> In September 2017, she was appointed [[President of the Supreme Court of the United Kingdom|President of the Supreme Court]] to succeed [[David Neuberger, Baron Neuberger of Abbotsbury|Lord Neuberger of Abbotsbury]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=62054|date=19 September 2017|page=17466}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March 2018, the [[Hong Kong]] judiciary announced her nomination as a non-permanent judge from other common law jurisdictions of the [[Court of Final Appeal of Hong Kong|Court of Final Appeal]]. Her appointment was accompanied by the appointments of [[Andrew Cheung]] and [[Beverley McLachlin]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thestandard.com.hk/breaking-news.php?id=104594&sid=4|title=Top court gets new judges|work=The Standard|access-date=21 March 2018|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180321194254/http://www.thestandard.com.hk/breaking-news.php?id=104594&sid=4|archive-date=21 March 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The appointment was gazetted by the [[Chief Executive of Hong Kong]] [[Carrie Lam]] and took effect 30 July 2018 for a three-year term.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gld.gov.hk/egazette/pdf/20182231/egn201822315815.pdf|title=Hong Kong Gazette Notice GN5815/2018|access-date=3 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904052542/https://www.gld.gov.hk/egazette/pdf/20182231/egn201822315815.pdf|archive-date=4 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2018, during an interview to mark the centenary of the [[Sex Disqualification (Removal) Act 1919]], Lady Hale argued that the judiciary needed to become more diverse so that the public have greater confidence in judges. Hale called for a more balanced gender representation on the UK's highest court and swifter progress promoting those from minority ethnic backgrounds and with \u201cless privileged lives\u201d. However, Hale objected to the idea of [[Affirmative action|positive discrimination]] because \u201cno one wants to feel they have got the job in any way other than on their own merits\u201d.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/law/2019/jan/01/lady-hale-supreme-court-president-judges-diversity|title=White and male UK judiciary \u2018from another planet\u2019, says Lady Hale|last=Bowcott|first=Owen|date=1 January 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=1 January 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190101005223/https://www.theguardian.com/law/2019/jan/01/lady-hale-supreme-court-president-judges-diversity|archive-date=1 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, as President of the [[Supreme Court of the United Kingdom]],  Lady Hale declared the prime minister [[Boris Johnson]]'s suspension of parliament unlawful.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/law/2019/sep/24/boris-johnsons-suspension-of-parliament-unlawful-supreme-court-rules-prorogue|title=Boris Johnson's suspension of parliament unlawful, supreme court rules|last=correspondent|first=Owen Bowcott Legal affairs|date=2019-09-24|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-11-25|last2=Quinn|first2=Ben|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|last3=Carrell|first3=Severin}}</ref> A ruling which Hale described as \"a source of, not pride, but satisfaction.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/law/2020/jan/11/lady-hale-desert-island-judgments-prorogation-case-simon-hattenstone|title=Lady Hale: 'My Desert Island Judgments? Number one would probably be the prorogation case'|last=Hattenstone|first=Simon|date=2020-01-11|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-01-13|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n==Significant lectures==\nOn 10 September 2015, she delivered the Caldwell Public Lecture at the [[University of Melbourne]], Australia, on the topic \"Protecting Human Rights in the UK Courts: What are we doing wrong?\".<ref>\"[http://www.trinity.unimelb.edu.au/about/news--media/events/caldwell-public-lecture-.html Caldwell Public Lecture] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151009025611/http://www.trinity.unimelb.edu.au/about/news--media/events/caldwell-public-lecture-.html |date=9 October 2015 }}\", Trinity College Events [online], accessed, 25 August 2015.</ref>\n\nOn 2 November 2018, she delivered an SLS Centenary Lecture at the University of Essex, United Kingdom, on the topic of \"All Human Beings? Reflection on the 70th Anniversary of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights\"\n\n==Honours==\n\n* She was appointed as a [[Queen's Counsel]] (QC) in 1989.\n* She was made a [[Order of the British Empire|Dame Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] (DBE) in the Civil Division in 1994. upon her appoint as a [[High Court of Justice|High Court Justice]]\n* She was sworn in  as a [[Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council|Member of Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council]] in 1999, giving her the [[Honorific|honorific title]] \"[[The Right Honourable]]\" for life.\n* On 12 January 2004 She was given a [[Life Peer|Life Peerage]] upon being appointed as a [[Lords of Appeal in Ordinary|Lord of Appeal in Ordinary]]. She took the title '''Baroness Hale of Richmond''', of [[Easby, Richmondshire|Easby]] in the County of [[North Yorkshire]]. She sat in the [[House of Lords]] as a [[Crossbencher]]. \n* She was elected as a [[Fellow of the British Academy|Fellow]] of the [[British Academy]] in 2004. This gave her the [[List of post-nominal letters (United Kingdom)|Post Nominal Letters]] \"FBA\" for Life.  <ref>https://www.thebritishacademy.ac.uk/fellows/brenda-hale-FBA-hon</ref>\n* The Law Building at the [[University of Salford]] was named after her in 2008.  <ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20110106041224/http://www.salford.ac.uk/news/details/1165</ref>\n\n{{Expand list|date=January 2020}}\n\n{{clear}}\n\n===Scholastic===\n; University degrees\n\n{| border=\"1\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"width:100%; margin:0.5em 1em 0.5em 0; border:1px #056 solid; border-collapse:collapse;\"\n|-\n!  style=\"background:#f5f5f5; width:20%;\"| <span style=\"color:dimGrey;\">Location</span> !!  style=\"background:#f5f5f5; width:20%;\"| <span style=\"color:dimGrey;\">Date</span> !!  style=\"background:#f5f5f5; width:40%;\"| <span style=\"color:dimGrey;\">School</span> !!  style=\"background:#f5f5f5; width:20%;\"| <span style=\"color:dimGrey;\">Degree</span>\n|-\n| {{Flagu|England}} || '''1966''' || [[Girton College, Cambridge]] || [[British undergraduate degree classification|Starred First]] [[Bachelor of Arts]]\n|-\n| {{Flagu|England}} || '''1969''' || [[Gray's Inn]] || [[Call to the bar|Called to the bar]]  <ref name=Guardian>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2004/jan/09/lords.women|work=The Guardian|title=The Guardian profile: Lady Brenda Hale|last=Dyer|first=Clare|accessdate=24 September 2019|date=9 January 2004|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161202010338/https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2004/jan/09/lords.women|archive-date=2 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=New>{{cite news|last=Stokel-Walker|first=Chris|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/brexit/2019/09/lady-hale-gently-determined-president-supreme-court-overruled-boris-johnson|work=New Statesman|date=24 September 2019|accessdate=24 September 2019|title=Lady Hale, the gently determined president of the Supreme Court that overruled Boris Johnson}}</ref>\n|- \n|}\n\n; Chancellor, visitor, governor, rector and fellowships\n{| border=\"1\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"width:100%; margin:0.5em 1em 0.5em 0; border:1px #056 solid; border-collapse:collapse;\"\n|-\n!  style=\"background:#f5f5f5; width:20%;\"| <span style=\"color:dimGrey;\">Location</span> !!  style=\"background:#f5f5f5; width:20%;\"| <span style=\"color:dimGrey;\">Date</span> !!  style=\"background:#f5f5f5; width:40%;\"| <span style=\"color:dimGrey;\">School</span> !!  style=\"background:#f5f5f5; width:20%;\"| <span style=\"color:dimGrey;\">Position</span>\n|-\n| {{Flagu|England}} || '''2004{{ndash}}present''' || [[Girton College, Cambridge]] || Visitor\n|-\n| {{Flagu|England}} || '''2004{{spaced ndash}}2016''' || [[University of Bristol]] || Chancellor\n|-\n| {{Flagu|England}} || '''2015{{spaced ndash}}present''' || [[Cambridge University Law Society|Law Society]] of the  [[University of Cambridge]] || Honorary President  <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.law.cam.ac.uk/press/events/2016/01/culs-lecture-lady-hale-life-lady-law-lord|title=CULS Lecture: Lady Hale \u2013 'The Life of A Lady Law Lord'|website=[[Faculty of Law, University of Cambridge]]|date=3 February 2016|access-date=10 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180110174810/https://www.law.cam.ac.uk/press/events/2016/01/culs-lecture-lady-hale-life-lady-law-lord|archive-date=10 January 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{Flagu|England}} || '''July 2017{{spaced ndash}}present''' || [[University of Bristol]] || [[Honorary title (academic)|Honorary Fellowship]]  <ref>https://www.bristol.ac.uk/graduation/honorary-degrees/honorary-fellows/hale/</ref>\n|-\n| {{Flagu|England}} || '''17 December 2019{{spaced ndash}}present''' || [[University College London]] || [[Honorary title (academic)|Honorary Law Professor]]  <ref>https://www.ucl.ac.uk/news/2019/dec/baroness-hale-appointed-honorary-professor-ucl</ref>\n|-\n| {{Flagu|England}} || '''2020{{spaced ndash}}present''' || [[Lady Margaret Hall, Oxford]] || [[Honorary title (academic)|Visiting Fellow]]  <ref>https://www.lmh.ox.ac.uk/visiting-fellows-2019</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n{{Expand list|date=January 2020}}\n\n;Honorary degrees\n{| border=\"1\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"width:100%; margin:0.5em 1em 0.5em 0; border:1px #056 solid; border-collapse:collapse;\"\n|-\n!  style=\"background:#f5f5f5; width:20%;\"| <span style=\"color:dimGrey;\">Location</span> !!  style=\"background:#f5f5f5; width:20%;\"| <span style=\"color:dimGrey;\">Date</span> !!  style=\"background:#f5f5f5; width:40%;\"| <span style=\"color:dimGrey;\">School</span> !!  style=\"background:#f5f5f5; width:20%;\"| <span style=\"color:dimGrey;\">Degree</span>\n|-\n| {{Flagu|England}} || '''2005''' || [[University of Cambridge]] || Doctorate  <ref>https://www.cam.ac.uk/about-the-university/how-the-university-and-colleges-work/processes/honorary-degrees/selected-honorands</ref>\n|-\n| {{Flagu|England}} || '''2006''' || [[University of Hull]] || [[Doctor of Laws]] (LL.D)  <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hull.ac.uk/work-with-us/more/media-centre/news/2019/supreme-court-president-inspires-university-of-hull-students.aspx|title=Supreme Court President inspires University of Hull students|publisher=University of Hull|date=5 March 2019|accessdate=24 September 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{Flagu|England}} || '''July 2007''' || [[University of Reading]] || [[Doctor of Laws]] (LL.D)  <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reading.ac.uk/web/files/Graduation/Baroness_Hale_speech_(final_version)_July_07.pdf|format=PDF|page=2|title=Presentation of the Rt Hon the Baroness Hale of Richmond|date=July 2007|accessdate=24 September 2019|publisher=University of Reading|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160415023600/https://www.reading.ac.uk/web/FILES/Graduation/Baroness_Hale_speech_(final_version)_July_07.pdf|archive-date=15 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{Flagu|England}} || '''27 February 2009''' || [[University of the West of England, Bristol|University of the West of England]] || [[Doctor of Laws]] (LL.D)  <ref>https://info.uwe.ac.uk/news/uwenews/news.aspx?id=1439</ref>\n|-\n| {{Flagu|England}} || '''July 2010''' || [[University of Salford]] || Doctorate  <ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20110106041224/http://www.salford.ac.uk/news/details/1165</ref>\n|-\n| {{Flagu|England}} || '''July 2011''' || [[University of Kent]] || [[Doctor of Laws]] (LL.D)  <ref>https://www.kent.ac.uk/congregations/honorary-grads/archive/2011/baronesshale.html</ref>  <ref>https://blogs.kent.ac.uk/ice-p/2017/10/06/kent-honorary-graduate-sworn-in-as-first-female-president-of-the-uks-supreme-court/</ref>\n|-\n| {{Flagu|England}} || '''2016''' || [[University of Worcester]] || Doctorate  <ref>https://www.worcester.ac.uk/about/news/president-of-supreme-court-to-consider-moral-courage-in-the-law-in-worcester-lecture.aspx</ref>\n|-\n| {{Flagu|England}} || '''2018''' || [[York St John University]] || [[Doctor of Laws]] (LL.D) <ref>https://www.yorksj.ac.uk/about/honorary-graduates/honorary-graduates--fellows-2018/</ref>\n|-\n| {{Flagu|England}} || '''26 July 2019''' || [[Edge Hill University]] || [[Doctor of Laws]] (LL.D)  <ref>https://www.edgehill.ac.uk/news/2019/07/the-first-female-president-of-the-uk-supreme-court-who-was-also-the-first-woman-and-the-youngest-person-to-be-appointed-to-the-law-commission-has-received-the-award-honorary-doctor-of-laws-from-edge/</ref>\n|-\n| {{Flagu|England}} || '''2019''' || [[University of Bradford]] || [[Doctor of Laws]] (LL.D) <ref>https://www.bradford.ac.uk/graduation/honorary-graduates/</ref> <ref>https://www.bradford.ac.uk/news/archive/2019/university-honours-eight-at-graduations.php</ref>\n|-\n| {{Flagu|England}} ||  || [[London School of Economics]] || [[Doctor of Laws]] (LL.D) <ref>http://www.lse.ac.uk/intranet/LSEServices/governanceAndCommittees/lse_honorary_degrees.aspx</ref>\n|-\n|}\n{{Expand list|date=January 2020}}\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1968, Hale married Anthony Hoggett, a fellow law lecturer at [[University of Manchester|Manchester]], with whom she had one daughter. The marriage was dissolved in 1992. In the same year, she married Julian Farrand, former dean of the law faculty at Manchester <ref name=Guardian/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.001.0001/ww-9780199540884-e-20455/version/2|publisher=UK Who's Who|accessdate=24 September 2019|title=Hoggett, Anthony John Christopher}}</ref>, and subsequently [[Pensions Ombudsman]].\n\nIn April 2018, Hale featured as a celebrity judge on [[BBC]] cooking show [[MasterChef (UK TV series)|''MasterChef'']].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/baroness-hale-to-lay-down-the-law-on-masterchef-df3pbtfz7|title=Baroness Hale to lay down the law on MasterChef|last=Editor|first=Frances Gibb, Legal|date=30 April 2018|work=The Times|access-date=5 April 2018|language=en|issn=0140-0460|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180406040501/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/baroness-hale-to-lay-down-the-law-on-masterchef-df3pbtfz7|archive-date=6 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n*''Parents and Children'' (1977, 2nd ed. 1981, Sweet and Maxwell) {{ISBN|9780421279100}}\n*''[[Women and the Law]]'' (as Brenda Hoggett, with [[Susan Atkins (civil servant)|Susan Atkins]], 1984, republished 2018, Institute of Advanced Legal studies, University of London) {{ISBN|9781911507109}}\n*''The Family, Law & Society'' (with [[David Pearl (lawyer)|David Pearl]], Elizabeth Cooke, Daniel Monk, 2009, Oxford University Press) {{ISBN|9780199204243}}\n*''Mental Health Law'' (2017, with Penelope Gorman, Rachel Barrett and Jessica Jones, Sweet & Maxwell, {{ISBN|9780414051201}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://society.guardian.co.uk/crimeandpunishment/story/0,8150,1119488,00.html Profile] from ''[[The Guardian]]'', 9 January 2004\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-legal}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Peter Millett, Baron Millett|The Lord Millett]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Lord of Appeal in Ordinary]]|years=2004\u20132009}}\n{{s-non|reason=Abolished}}\n{{s-new|office}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Justice of the Supreme Court of the United Kingdom|Justice of the Supreme Court]]|years=2009\u20132013}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Patrick Hodge, Lord Hodge|Lord Hodge]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[David Hope, Baron Hope of Craighead|The Lord Hope of Craighead]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Deputy President of the Supreme Court of the United Kingdom|Deputy President of the Supreme Court]]|years=2013\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jonathan Mance, Baron Mance|The Lord Mance]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[David Neuberger, Baron Neuberger of Abbotsbury|The Lord Neuberger of Abbotsbury]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[President of the Supreme Court of the United Kingdom|President of the Supreme Court]]|years=2017\u20132020}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Robert Reed, Baron Reed of Allermuir|The Lord Reed of Allermuir]]}}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Visitor of [[Girton College, Cambridge]]|years=2004\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jeremy Morse|Sir Jeremy Morse]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chancellor of the [[University of Bristol]]|years=2004\u20132016}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Paul Nurse|Sir Paul Nurse]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Supreme Court of the United Kingdom}}\n{{Longford Lecturers}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hale Of Richmond, Brenda Hale, Baroness}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Academics of King's College London]]\n[[Category:Academics of the Victoria University of Manchester]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Girton College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:British Queen's Counsel]]\n[[Category:British women lawyers]]\n[[Category:Chancellors of the University of Bristol]]\n[[Category:Dames Commander of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Deputy Presidents of the Supreme Court of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:English barristers]]\n[[Category:English legal scholars]]\n[[Category:English legal writers]]\n[[Category:English women judges]]\n[[Category:Family Division judges]]\n[[Category:Fellows of Girton College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the British Academy]]\n[[Category:Female life peers]]\n[[Category:Justices of the Court of Final Appeal (Hong Kong)]]\n[[Category:Judges of the Supreme Court of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Lady Justices of Appeal]]\n[[Category:Law lords]]\n[[Category:Members of Gray's Inn]]\n[[Category:Members of the Judicial Committee of the Privy Council]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Supreme Court of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Queen's Counsel 1901\u20132000]]\n[[Category:Writers from Leeds]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = The Baroness Hale of Richmond\n| honorific-suffix = {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|DBE|PC|FBA}}\n| image = Baroness Hale of Richmond 2019.jpg\n| office = [[President of the Supreme Court of the United Kingdom]]\n| term_start = 5 September 2017\n| term_end = 11 January 2020\n| deputy = {{Unbulleted list |[[Jonathan Mance, Baron Mance|Lord Mance]] |[[Robert Reed, Lord Reed|Lord Reed]]}}\n| predecessor = [[David Neuberger, Baron Neuberger of Abbotsbury|Lord Neuberger]]\n| successor = [[Robert Reed, Lord Reed]]\n| office1 = [[Deputy President of the Supreme Court of the United Kingdom]]\n| term_start1 = 28 June 2013\n| term_end1 = 4 September 2017\n| monarch = [[Elizabeth II]]\n| predecessor1 = [[David Hope, Baron Hope of Craighead|Lord Hope]]\n| president1 = [[David Neuberger, Baron Neuberger of Abbotsbury|Lord Neuberger]]\n| successor1 = [[Jonathan Mance, Baron Mance|Lord Mance]]\n| office2 = [[Judges of the Supreme Court of the United Kingdom|Justice of the Supreme Court of the United Kingdom]]\n| term_start2 = 1 October 2009\n| term_end2 = 10 January 2020\n| predecessor2 = ''Position created''\n| successor2 = [[Nicholas Hamblen, Lord Hamblen]]\n| office3 = [[Lord of Appeal in Ordinary]]\n| term_start3 = 12 January 2004\n| term_end3 = 30 September 2009\n| predecessor3 = [[Peter Millett, Baron Millett|Lord Millett]]\n| successor3 = ''Position abolished''\n| office4 = [[Lady Justice of Appeal]]\n| term_start4 = 1999\n| term_end4 = 2003\n| office5 = [[High Court judge (England and Wales)|High Court Judge<br />Family Division]]\n| term_start5 = 1994\n| term_end5 = 1999\n| appointer5 = [[Elizabeth II]]\n| predecessor4 = \n| office6 = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br/><small>[[Lords Temporal|Lord Temporal (Judicial Peer)]]</small>\n| term_start6 = 12 January 2004\n| term_end6 = 1 October 2009\n| title7 = Chancellor of the [[University of Bristol]]\n| order7 = 7th\n| term_start7 = 2004\n| term_end7 = 2017\n| predecessor7 = Sir [[Jeremy Morse]]\n| successor7 = Sir [[Paul Nurse]]\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1945|01|31}}\n| birth_place = [[Leeds]], [[West Riding of Yorkshire]], England\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| restingplace = \n| birthname = Brenda Marjorie Hale\n| spouse = {{unbulleted list | {{marriage|Anthony Hoggett|1968|1992|end=div}} | {{marriage|Julian Farrand |1992}}}}\n| children = 1\n| residence = \n| alma_mater = [[Girton College, Cambridge]]\n| office8 = Non-Permanent Judge of the [[Court of Final Appeal (Hong Kong)|Court of Final Appeal]] of Hong Kong\n| term_start8 = 30 July 2018\n| term_end8 = \n}}\n\n'''Brenda Marjorie Hale, Baroness Hale of Richmond''', {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|DBE|PC|FBA|sep= }} (born 31 January 1945), known as '''Lady Hale''', is a British judge who served as [[President of the Supreme Court of the United Kingdom]] from 2017 to 2020.<ref>[http://www.judiciary.gov.uk/keyfacts/list_judiciary/senior_judiciary_list.htm Senior Judiciary List] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120618220245/http://www.judiciary.gov.uk/about-the-judiciary/judges-magistrates-and-tribunal-judges/list-of-members-of-the-judiciary/senior-judiciary-list |date=18 June 2012 }}, Ministry of Justice.</ref>\n\nIn 2004, she joined the [[House of Lords]] as a  [[Lord of Appeal in Ordinary]]. She is the only woman to have been appointed to that position. She served as a Law Lord until 2009 when she, along with the other Law Lords, transferred to the new [[Supreme Court of the United Kingdom|Supreme Court]] as a result of the [[Constitutional Reform Act 2005]]. She served as [[Deputy President of the Supreme Court of the United Kingdom|Deputy President of the Supreme Court]] from 2013 to 2017.\n\nOn 5 September 2017, Hale was appointed under the Premiership of [[Theresa May]] to serve as [[President of the Supreme Court of the United Kingdom|President of the Supreme Court]], and was sworn in on 2 October 2017. She is the third person and first woman to serve in the role. Hale is one of three women to have been appointed to the Supreme Court (alongside [[Jill Black, Lady Black of Derwent|Lady Black]] and [[Mary Arden, Lady Arden|Lady Arden]]).\n\nSince 30 July 2018, Hale has been a non-permanent judge of the [[Court of Final Appeal (Hong Kong)|Court of Final Appeal of Hong Kong]]. Hale has also been Honorary President of the [[Cambridge University Law Society]] since 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.law.cam.ac.uk/press/events/2016/01/culs-lecture-lady-hale-life-lady-law-lord|title=CULS Lecture: Lady Hale \u2013 'The Life of A Lady Law Lord'|website=[[Faculty of Law, University of Cambridge]]|date=3 February 2016|access-date=10 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180110174810/https://www.law.cam.ac.uk/press/events/2016/01/culs-lecture-lady-hale-life-lady-law-lord|archive-date=10 January 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn the 11th January 2020, Lady Hale was succeeded by Lord Reed as President of Supreme Court.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.legalcheek.com/2020/01/lord-reed-sworn-in-as-new-supreme-court-president/|title=Lord Reed sworn in as new Supreme Court president|date=2020-01-13|website=Legal Cheek|access-date=2020-01-13}}</ref> \n\n==Early life==\nBrenda Marjorie Hale<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.supremecourt.uk/about/biographies-of-the-justices.html|publisher=Supreme Court of the United Kingdom|accessdate=24 September 2019|title=Biographies of the Justices|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190522153902/https://www.supremecourt.uk/about/biographies-of-the-justices.html|archive-date=22 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> was born on 31 January 1945 in [[Leeds]], [[West Riding of Yorkshire]]. Both her parents were headteachers. She has two sisters. Hale lived in [[Redcar]] until the age of three when she moved with her parents to [[Richmond, North Yorkshire]]. She was educated at the Richmond High School for Girls (now part of [[Richmond School]]), where she and her two sisters were all [[head girl]]s.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Amos |first1=Mike |title=Judge not lest thou be judged, but the column\u2019s still much impressed by Lady Hale |url=https://www.theboltonnews.co.uk/news/16182345.amp/ |accessdate=27 December 2019 |work=[[Bolton News]] |date=5 April 2018}}</ref> She later studied at [[Girton College, Cambridge]] (the first from her school to attend Cambridge), where she read law. Hale was one of six women in her class, which had 110 men, and graduated with a [[British undergraduate degree classification#Variations of first-class honours|starred first]] and top of her class in 1966.<ref name=Guardian/><ref name=New/>\n\nAfter becoming an assistant law lecturer at the [[Victoria University of Manchester]] (now the [[University of Manchester]]), she was [[Call to the bar|called to the Bar]] by [[Gray's Inn]] in 1969, topping the list in the bar finals for that year.<ref name=Guardian>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2004/jan/09/lords.women|work=The Guardian|title=The Guardian profile: Lady Brenda Hale|last=Dyer|first=Clare|accessdate=24 September 2019|date=9 January 2004|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161202010338/https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2004/jan/09/lords.women|archive-date=2 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=New>{{cite news|last=Stokel-Walker|first=Chris|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/brexit/2019/09/lady-hale-gently-determined-president-supreme-court-overruled-boris-johnson|work=New Statesman|date=24 September 2019|accessdate=24 September 2019|title=Lady Hale, the gently determined president of the Supreme Court that overruled Boris Johnson}}</ref>\n\nWorking part-time as a [[barrister]], Hale spent 18 years mostly in academia, becoming Professor of Law at Manchester in 1986. Two years earlier, she became the first woman and youngest person to be appointed to the [[Law Commission (England and Wales)|Law Commission]], overseeing a number of important reforms<ref name=\"NYT 92419\">{{cite news |author1=Yonette Joseph |author2=Ceylan Yeginsu |title=Lady Hale, U.K. Supreme Court Judge, Speaks Calmly and Brings Down the Hammer |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/24/world/europe/lady-hale-supreme-court-uk.html |accessdate=September 24, 2019 |work=The New York Times |date=24 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190925082602/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/24/world/europe/lady-hale-supreme-court-uk.html |archive-date=25 September 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> in [[family law]] during her nine years with the Commission. In 1989, she was appointed [[Queen's Counsel]].<ref name=Guardian/>\n\n==Judicial career==\nHale was appointed a [[Recorder (judge)|Recorder]] (a part-time [[Circuit judge (UK)|circuit judge]]) in 1989, and in 1994 became a [[High Court judge (England and Wales)|judge]] in the Family Division of the [[High Court of Justice of England and Wales|High Court of Justice]] (styled The Honourable Mrs Justice Hale).<ref name=Guardian/> Upon her appointment, as is convention, she was appointed a [[Order of the British Empire|Dame Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] (DBE). In 1999, Hale followed [[Elizabeth Butler-Sloss, Baroness Butler-Sloss|Dame Elizabeth Butler-Sloss]] to become only the second woman to be appointed to the [[Court of Appeal of England and Wales|Court of Appeal]] (styled The Right Honourable Lady Justice Hale), entering the [[Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council|Privy Council]] at the same time.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/law/2017/jul/21/brenda-hale-to-become-supreme-courts-first-female-president-reports|work=The Guardian|title=Brenda Hale to become first female president of supreme court \u2013 reports|last=Slawson|first=Nicola|date=21 July 2017|accessdate=24 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181230180612/https://www.theguardian.com/law/2017/jul/21/brenda-hale-to-become-supreme-courts-first-female-president-reports|archive-date=30 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 January 2004, she was appointed the first female [[Lord of Appeal in Ordinary]] and was created a life peer as '''Baroness Hale of Richmond''', of Easby in the County of North Yorkshire,<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=57179 |page=503 |date=15 January 2004}}</ref> under the [[Appellate Jurisdiction Act 1876]].<ref name=Supreme/>\n\nIn June 2013, she was appointed [[Deputy President of the Supreme Court of the United Kingdom]] to succeed [[David Hope, Baron Hope of Craighead|Lord Hope of Craighead]].<ref name=Supreme>{{cite web|url=https://www.supremecourt.uk/news/lady-hale-to-be-next-deputy-president-of-supreme-court.html|title=Lady Hale to be next Deputy President of Supreme Court|publisher=Supreme Court of the United Kingdom|date=24 June 2013|accessdate=24 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140205090531/http://supremecourt.uk/news/lady-hale-to-be-next-deputy-president-of-supreme-court.html|archive-date=5 February 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> In September 2017, she was appointed [[President of the Supreme Court of the United Kingdom|President of the Supreme Court]] to succeed [[David Neuberger, Baron Neuberger of Abbotsbury|Lord Neuberger of Abbotsbury]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=62054|date=19 September 2017|page=17466}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March 2018, the [[Hong Kong]] judiciary announced her nomination as a non-permanent judge from other common law jurisdictions of the [[Court of Final Appeal of Hong Kong|Court of Final Appeal]]. Her appointment was accompanied by the appointments of [[Andrew Cheung]] and [[Beverley McLachlin]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thestandard.com.hk/breaking-news.php?id=104594&sid=4|title=Top court gets new judges|work=The Standard|access-date=21 March 2018|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180321194254/http://www.thestandard.com.hk/breaking-news.php?id=104594&sid=4|archive-date=21 March 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The appointment was gazetted by the [[Chief Executive of Hong Kong]] [[Carrie Lam]] and took effect 30 July 2018 for a three-year term.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gld.gov.hk/egazette/pdf/20182231/egn201822315815.pdf|title=Hong Kong Gazette Notice GN5815/2018|access-date=3 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180904052542/https://www.gld.gov.hk/egazette/pdf/20182231/egn201822315815.pdf|archive-date=4 September 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2018, during an interview to mark the centenary of the [[Sex Disqualification (Removal) Act 1919]], Lady Hale argued that the judiciary needed to become more diverse so that the public have greater confidence in judges. Hale called for a more balanced gender representation on the UK's highest court and swifter progress promoting those from minority ethnic backgrounds and with \u201cless privileged lives\u201d. However, Hale objected to the idea of [[Affirmative action|positive discrimination]] because \u201cno one wants to feel they have got the job in any way other than on their own merits\u201d.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/law/2019/jan/01/lady-hale-supreme-court-president-judges-diversity|title=White and male UK judiciary \u2018from another planet\u2019, says Lady Hale|last=Bowcott|first=Owen|date=1 January 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=1 January 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190101005223/https://www.theguardian.com/law/2019/jan/01/lady-hale-supreme-court-president-judges-diversity|archive-date=1 January 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, as President of the [[Supreme Court of the United Kingdom]],  Lady Hale declared the prime minister [[Boris Johnson]]'s suspension of parliament unlawful.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/law/2019/sep/24/boris-johnsons-suspension-of-parliament-unlawful-supreme-court-rules-prorogue|title=Boris Johnson's suspension of parliament unlawful, supreme court rules|last=correspondent|first=Owen Bowcott Legal affairs|date=2019-09-24|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-11-25|last2=Quinn|first2=Ben|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|last3=Carrell|first3=Severin}}</ref> A ruling which Hale described as \"a source of, not pride, but satisfaction.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/law/2020/jan/11/lady-hale-desert-island-judgments-prorogation-case-simon-hattenstone|title=Lady Hale: 'My Desert Island Judgments? Number one would probably be the prorogation case'|last=Hattenstone|first=Simon|date=2020-01-11|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-01-13|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n==Significant lectures==\nOn 10 September 2015, she delivered the Caldwell Public Lecture at the [[University of Melbourne]], Australia, on the topic \"Protecting Human Rights in the UK Courts: What are we doing wrong?\".<ref>\"[http://www.trinity.unimelb.edu.au/about/news--media/events/caldwell-public-lecture-.html Caldwell Public Lecture] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151009025611/http://www.trinity.unimelb.edu.au/about/news--media/events/caldwell-public-lecture-.html |date=9 October 2015 }}\", Trinity College Events [online], accessed, 25 August 2015.</ref>\n\nOn 2 November 2018, she delivered an SLS Centenary Lecture at the University of Essex, United Kingdom, on the topic of \"All Human Beings? Reflection on the 70th Anniversary of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights\"\n\n==Honours==\n\n* She was appointed as a [[Queen's Counsel]] (QC) in 1989.\n* She was made a [[Order of the British Empire|Dame Commander of the Order of the British Empire]] (DBE) in the Civil Division in 1994. upon her appoint as a [[High Court of Justice|High Court Justice]]\n* She was sworn in  as a [[Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council|Member of Her Majesty's Most Honourable Privy Council]] in 1999, giving her the [[Honorific|honorific title]] \"[[The Right Honourable]]\" for life.\n* On 12 January 2004 She was given a [[Life Peer|Life Peerage]] upon being appointed as a [[Lords of Appeal in Ordinary|Lord of Appeal in Ordinary]]. She took the title '''Baroness Hale of Richmond''', of [[Easby, Richmondshire|Easby]] in the County of [[North Yorkshire]]. She sat in the [[House of Lords]] as a [[Crossbencher]]. \n* She was elected as a [[Fellow of the British Academy|Fellow]] of the [[British Academy]] in 2004. This gave her the [[List of post-nominal letters (United Kingdom)|Post Nominal Letters]] \"FBA\" for Life.  <ref>https://www.thebritishacademy.ac.uk/fellows/brenda-hale-FBA-hon</ref>\n* The Law Building at the [[University of Salford]] was named after her in 2008.  <ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20110106041224/http://www.salford.ac.uk/news/details/1165</ref>\n\n{{Expand list|date=January 2020}}\n\n{{clear}}\n\n===Scholastic===\n; University degrees\n\n{| border=\"1\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"width:100%; margin:0.5em 1em 0.5em 0; border:1px #056 solid; border-collapse:collapse;\"\n|-\n!  style=\"background:#f5f5f5; width:20%;\"| <span style=\"color:dimGrey;\">Location</span> !!  style=\"background:#f5f5f5; width:20%;\"| <span style=\"color:dimGrey;\">Date</span> !!  style=\"background:#f5f5f5; width:40%;\"| <span style=\"color:dimGrey;\">School</span> !!  style=\"background:#f5f5f5; width:20%;\"| <span style=\"color:dimGrey;\">Degree</span>\n|-\n| {{Flagu|England}} || '''1966''' || [[Girton College, Cambridge]] || [[British undergraduate degree classification|Starred First]] [[Bachelor of Arts]]\n|-\n| {{Flagu|England}} || '''1969''' || [[Gray's Inn]] || [[Call to the bar|Called to the bar]]  <ref name=Guardian>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2004/jan/09/lords.women|work=The Guardian|title=The Guardian profile: Lady Brenda Hale|last=Dyer|first=Clare|accessdate=24 September 2019|date=9 January 2004|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161202010338/https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2004/jan/09/lords.women|archive-date=2 December 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=New>{{cite news|last=Stokel-Walker|first=Chris|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/brexit/2019/09/lady-hale-gently-determined-president-supreme-court-overruled-boris-johnson|work=New Statesman|date=24 September 2019|accessdate=24 September 2019|title=Lady Hale, the gently determined president of the Supreme Court that overruled Boris Johnson}}</ref>\n|- \n|}\n\n; Chancellor, visitor, governor, rector and fellowships\n{| border=\"1\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"width:100%; margin:0.5em 1em 0.5em 0; border:1px #056 solid; border-collapse:collapse;\"\n|-\n!  style=\"background:#f5f5f5; width:20%;\"| <span style=\"color:dimGrey;\">Location</span> !!  style=\"background:#f5f5f5; width:20%;\"| <span style=\"color:dimGrey;\">Date</span> !!  style=\"background:#f5f5f5; width:40%;\"| <span style=\"color:dimGrey;\">School</span> !!  style=\"background:#f5f5f5; width:20%;\"| <span style=\"color:dimGrey;\">Position</span>\n|-\n| {{Flagu|England}} || '''2004{{ndash}}present''' || [[Girton College, Cambridge]] || Visitor\n|-\n| {{Flagu|England}} || '''2004{{spaced ndash}}2016''' || [[University of Bristol]] || Chancellor\n|-\n| {{Flagu|England}} || '''2015{{spaced ndash}}present''' || [[Cambridge University Law Society|Law Society]] of the  [[University of Cambridge]] || Honorary President  <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.law.cam.ac.uk/press/events/2016/01/culs-lecture-lady-hale-life-lady-law-lord|title=CULS Lecture: Lady Hale \u2013 'The Life of A Lady Law Lord'|website=[[Faculty of Law, University of Cambridge]]|date=3 February 2016|access-date=10 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180110174810/https://www.law.cam.ac.uk/press/events/2016/01/culs-lecture-lady-hale-life-lady-law-lord|archive-date=10 January 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{Flagu|England}} || '''July 2017{{spaced ndash}}present''' || [[University of Bristol]] || [[Honorary title (academic)|Honorary Fellowship]]  <ref>https://www.bristol.ac.uk/graduation/honorary-degrees/honorary-fellows/hale/</ref>\n|-\n| {{Flagu|England}} || '''17 December 2019{{spaced ndash}}present''' || [[University College London]] || [[Honorary title (academic)|Honorary Law Professor]]  <ref>https://www.ucl.ac.uk/news/2019/dec/baroness-hale-appointed-honorary-professor-ucl</ref>\n|-\n| {{Flagu|England}} || '''2020{{spaced ndash}}present''' || [[Lady Margaret Hall, Oxford]] || [[Honorary title (academic)|Visiting Fellow]]  <ref>https://www.lmh.ox.ac.uk/visiting-fellows-2019</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n{{Expand list|date=January 2020}}\n\n;Honorary degrees\n{| border=\"1\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"width:100%; margin:0.5em 1em 0.5em 0; border:1px #056 solid; border-collapse:collapse;\"\n|-\n!  style=\"background:#f5f5f5; width:20%;\"| <span style=\"color:dimGrey;\">Location</span> !!  style=\"background:#f5f5f5; width:20%;\"| <span style=\"color:dimGrey;\">Date</span> !!  style=\"background:#f5f5f5; width:40%;\"| <span style=\"color:dimGrey;\">School</span> !!  style=\"background:#f5f5f5; width:20%;\"| <span style=\"color:dimGrey;\">Degree</span>\n|-\n| {{Flagu|England}} || '''2005''' || [[University of Cambridge]] || Doctorate  <ref>https://www.cam.ac.uk/about-the-university/how-the-university-and-colleges-work/processes/honorary-degrees/selected-honorands</ref>\n|-\n| {{Flagu|England}} || '''2006''' || [[University of Hull]] || [[Doctor of Laws]] (LL.D)  <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hull.ac.uk/work-with-us/more/media-centre/news/2019/supreme-court-president-inspires-university-of-hull-students.aspx|title=Supreme Court President inspires University of Hull students|publisher=University of Hull|date=5 March 2019|accessdate=24 September 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{Flagu|England}} || '''July 2007''' || [[University of Reading]] || [[Doctor of Laws]] (LL.D)  <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reading.ac.uk/web/files/Graduation/Baroness_Hale_speech_(final_version)_July_07.pdf|format=PDF|page=2|title=Presentation of the Rt Hon the Baroness Hale of Richmond|date=July 2007|accessdate=24 September 2019|publisher=University of Reading|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160415023600/https://www.reading.ac.uk/web/FILES/Graduation/Baroness_Hale_speech_(final_version)_July_07.pdf|archive-date=15 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{Flagu|England}} || '''27 February 2009''' || [[University of the West of England, Bristol|University of the West of England]] || [[Doctor of Laws]] (LL.D)  <ref>https://info.uwe.ac.uk/news/uwenews/news.aspx?id=1439</ref>\n|-\n| {{Flagu|England}} || '''July 2010''' || [[University of Salford]] || Doctorate  <ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20110106041224/http://www.salford.ac.uk/news/details/1165</ref>\n|-\n| {{Flagu|England}} || '''July 2011''' || [[University of Kent]] || [[Doctor of Laws]] (LL.D)  <ref>https://www.kent.ac.uk/congregations/honorary-grads/archive/2011/baronesshale.html</ref>  <ref>https://blogs.kent.ac.uk/ice-p/2017/10/06/kent-honorary-graduate-sworn-in-as-first-female-president-of-the-uks-supreme-court/</ref>\n|-\n| {{Flagu|England}} || '''2016''' || [[University of Worcester]] || Doctorate  <ref>https://www.worcester.ac.uk/about/news/president-of-supreme-court-to-consider-moral-courage-in-the-law-in-worcester-lecture.aspx</ref>\n|-\n| {{Flagu|England}} || '''2018''' || [[York St John University]] || [[Doctor of Laws]] (LL.D) <ref>https://www.yorksj.ac.uk/about/honorary-graduates/honorary-graduates--fellows-2018/</ref>\n|-\n| {{Flagu|England}} || '''26 July 2019''' || [[Edge Hill University]] || [[Doctor of Laws]] (LL.D)  <ref>https://www.edgehill.ac.uk/news/2019/07/the-first-female-president-of-the-uk-supreme-court-who-was-also-the-first-woman-and-the-youngest-person-to-be-appointed-to-the-law-commission-has-received-the-award-honorary-doctor-of-laws-from-edge/</ref>\n|-\n| {{Flagu|England}} || '''2019''' || [[University of Bradford]] || [[Doctor of Laws]] (LL.D) <ref>https://www.bradford.ac.uk/graduation/honorary-graduates/</ref> <ref>https://www.bradford.ac.uk/news/archive/2019/university-honours-eight-at-graduations.php</ref>\n|-\n| {{Flagu|England}} ||  || [[London School of Economics]] || [[Doctor of Laws]] (LL.D) <ref>http://www.lse.ac.uk/intranet/LSEServices/governanceAndCommittees/lse_honorary_degrees.aspx</ref>\n|-\n|}\n{{Expand list|date=January 2020}}\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 1968, Hale married Anthony Hoggett, a fellow law lecturer at [[University of Manchester|Manchester]], with whom she had one daughter. The marriage was dissolved in 1992. In the same year, she married Julian Farrand, former dean of the law faculty at Manchester <ref name=Guardian/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.001.0001/ww-9780199540884-e-20455/version/2|publisher=UK Who's Who|accessdate=24 September 2019|title=Hoggett, Anthony John Christopher}}</ref>, and subsequently [[Pensions Ombudsman]].\n\nIn April 2018, Hale featured as a celebrity judge on [[BBC]] cooking show [[MasterChef (UK TV series)|''MasterChef'']].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/baroness-hale-to-lay-down-the-law-on-masterchef-df3pbtfz7|title=Baroness Hale to lay down the law on MasterChef|last=Editor|first=Frances Gibb, Legal|date=30 April 2018|work=The Times|access-date=5 April 2018|language=en|issn=0140-0460|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180406040501/https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/baroness-hale-to-lay-down-the-law-on-masterchef-df3pbtfz7|archive-date=6 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n*''Parents and Children'' (1977, 2nd ed. 1981, Sweet and Maxwell) {{ISBN|9780421279100}}\n*''[[Women and the Law]]'' (as Brenda Hoggett, with [[Susan Atkins (civil servant)|Susan Atkins]], 1984, republished 2018, Institute of Advanced Legal studies, University of London) {{ISBN|9781911507109}}\n*''The Family, Law & Society'' (with [[David Pearl (lawyer)|David Pearl]], Elizabeth Cooke, Daniel Monk, 2009, Oxford University Press) {{ISBN|9780199204243}}\n*''Mental Health Law'' (2017, with Penelope Gorman, Rachel Barrett and Jessica Jones, Sweet & Maxwell, {{ISBN|9780414051201}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://society.guardian.co.uk/crimeandpunishment/story/0,8150,1119488,00.html Profile] from ''[[The Guardian]]'', 9 January 2004\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-legal}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Peter Millett, Baron Millett|The Lord Millett]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Lord of Appeal in Ordinary]]|years=2004\u20132009}}\n{{s-non|reason=Abolished}}\n{{s-new|office}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Justice of the Supreme Court of the United Kingdom|Justice of the Supreme Court]]|years=2009\u20132013}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Patrick Hodge, Lord Hodge|Lord Hodge]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[David Hope, Baron Hope of Craighead|The Lord Hope of Craighead]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Deputy President of the Supreme Court of the United Kingdom|Deputy President of the Supreme Court]]|years=2013\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jonathan Mance, Baron Mance|The Lord Mance]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[David Neuberger, Baron Neuberger of Abbotsbury|The Lord Neuberger of Abbotsbury]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[President of the Supreme Court of the United Kingdom|President of the Supreme Court]]|years=2017\u20132020}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Robert Reed, Baron Reed of Allermuir|The Lord Reed of Allermuir]]}}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Visitor of [[Girton College, Cambridge]]|years=2004\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jeremy Morse|Sir Jeremy Morse]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chancellor of the [[University of Bristol]]|years=2004\u20132016}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Paul Nurse|Sir Paul Nurse]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Supreme Court of the United Kingdom}}\n{{Longford Lecturers}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hale Of Richmond, Brenda Hale, Baroness}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Academics of King's College London]]\n[[Category:Academics of the Victoria University of Manchester]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Girton College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:British Queen's Counsel]]\n[[Category:British women lawyers]]\n[[Category:Chancellors of the University of Bristol]]\n[[Category:Dames Commander of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Deputy Presidents of the Supreme Court of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:English barristers]]\n[[Category:English legal scholars]]\n[[Category:English legal writers]]\n[[Category:English women judges]]\n[[Category:Family Division judges]]\n[[Category:Fellows of Girton College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the British Academy]]\n[[Category:Female life peers]]\n[[Category:Justices of the Court of Final Appeal (Hong Kong)]]\n[[Category:Judges of the Supreme Court of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Lady Justices of Appeal]]\n[[Category:Law lords]]\n[[Category:Members of Gray's Inn]]\n[[Category:Members of the Judicial Committee of the Privy Council]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Supreme Court of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Queen's Counsel 1901\u20132000]]\n[[Category:Writers from Leeds]]\n", "name_user": "Anderlaxe", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added peerage after retirement.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brenda_Hale,_Baroness_Hale_of_Richmond"}
{"title_page": "RAF Chilbolton", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox airport \n| name = RAF Chilbolton<br>USAAF Station AAF-404\n| nativename =  [[File:Ensign of the Royal Air Force.svg|90px]][[File:Patch9thusaaf.png|60px]]\n| nativename-a = \n| nativename-r = \n| image = Chilbolton-20apr44.jpg\n| image-width = 250px\n| caption = Aerial Photo of Chilbolton Airfield - 20 April 1944   \n| IATA = \n| ICAO = \n| type = Military   \n| owner = [[Air Ministry]]   \n| operator = [[Royal Air Force]]<br>[[United States Army Air Forces]]\n| city-served = \n| location = [[Chilbolton]], [[Hampshire]]\n| built = {{Start date|1938}}\n| used = 1940-{{End date|1946}}\n| elevation-f = {{Convert|84|m|disp=output number only|0}}\n| elevation-m = 84\n| coordinates = {{coord|51|08|36|N|001|26|23|W|region:GB_type:airport|display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_map = Hampshire\n| pushpin_label = RAF Chilbolton\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location in Hampshire\n| website = \n| r1-number = 02/20\n| r1-length-f = 4,800\n| r1-length-m = 0\n| r1-surface = [[Asphalt]]   \n| r2-number = 06/24\n| r2-length-f = 4,200\n| r2-length-m = 0\n| r2-surface = Asphalt \n| r3-number = 12/30\n| r3-length-f = 5,400\n| r3-length-m = 0\n| r3-surface = Asphalt \n| stat-year = \n| stat1-header = \n| stat1-data = \n| stat2-header = \n| stat2-data = \n}}\n[[File:Chil-p47-368fg.jpg|thumb|Republic P-47D-30-RE Thunderbolt Serial 44-20456 of the 397th Fighter Squadron on an escort mission over the German Alps.]]\n[[File:Chil-442tcg-1.jpg|thumb|Chilbolton loaded with CG-4As and C-47s to use in Operation \"Market\", September 1944.]]\n[[File:Chil-cg4a-442tcg.jpg|thumb|Closeup of CG-4As marshalled at Chilbolton in early September 1944 ready to be used in Operation \"Market\". Many of these gliders had been used in the 6 June D-Day invasion.]]\n\n'''Royal Air Force Station Chilbolton''' or '''RAF Chilbolton''' is a former [[Royal Air Force]] [[Royal Air Force station|station]] in [[Hampshire]], [[England]].  The airfield is located in [[Chilbolton]] approximately {{convert|4|mi|km}} south-southeast of [[Andover, Hampshire|Andover]]; about {{convert|62|mi|km}} southwest of [[London]]\n\nOpened in 1940, it was used by both the [[Royal Air Force]] and then later by the [[United States Army Air Forces]].  During the war it was used primarily as a troop carrier airfield for parachutists.  After the war it was used for military jet aircraft training before closing as an RAF station in 1946, although it was then used until the early 1960s by the Vickers-Supermarine and Folland aircraft companies for flight testing and development flying.\n\nToday the remains of the airfield are located on private property being used as agricultural fields.\n\n==History==\n\n===Royal Air Force use===\nRAF Chilbolton was opened in September 1940 as a satellite of [[RAF Middle Wallop]] and was used as a relief landing ground by the [[Royal Air Force]] (RAF).  At first it was developed piecemeal with the addition of the necessary facilities that took it towards existence as an independent airfield.  It then hosted its own [[Hawker Hurricane]] squadrons which took part in the [[Battle of Britain]].  [[No. 238 Squadron RAF]] operated throughout the Battle of Britain from Middle Wallop and [[RAF St Eval]] as part of [[No. 10 Group RAF|No. 10 Group]] Fighter Command, posted to Chilbolton in September 1940 with Hurricane Is.\n\nDuring the Battle of Britain many sorties were flown covering [[Southampton]] to [[Bristol]].\nOnce the battle had been won and therefore the threat of invasion had passed major [[Luftwaffe]] raids ceased.  Several [[Supermarine Spitfire]] and Hurricane squadrons came and went, none stayed very long.\n\nBy late 1941 Chilbolton had been upgraded with the addition of a perimeter track and several fighter concrete dispersal pens around it.\n\nBy November 1941 it was placed into Care and Maintenance as there was no use for it by then as the Battle of Britain had ended and there were sufficient airfields in the area to continue the war without it.\n\nRAF Units stationed at Chilbolton:\n* [[No. 238 Squadron RAF|238 Sqn]], Hurricane I, arrived 30 September 1940, departed 20 May 1941.\n* Glider Pilots Exercise Unit, [[de Havilland Tiger Moth]]/[[Miles Master]]/[[General Aircraft Hotspur]] arrived Dec-Jan 1941.\n* 238 Sqn, Hurricane IIA, arrived 1 February 1941, departed April 1941.\n* [[No. 308 Squadron RAF|308 Sqn]], Spitfire IIA, arrived 31 May 1941, departed 24 June 1941.\n* [[No. 501 Squadron RAF|501 Sqn]], Spitfire IIA, arrived 25 June 1941, departed 5 August 1941.\n* [[No. 504 Squadron RAF|504 Sqn]], Hurricane IIB, arrived 11 August 1941, departed 26 August 1941.\n* [[No. 245 Squadron RAF|245 Sqn]], Hurricane IIB, arrived 1 September 1941, departed 17 Nov 1941.\n* 245 Sqn, Hurricane IIB, arrived 23 Nov 1941, departed 19 Dec 1941.\n* [[No. 184 Squadron RAF|184 Sqn]], Hurricane IID, arrived 1 March 1943, departed 11 March 1943.\n* [[No. 174 Squadron RAF|174 Sqn]], Hurricane IIB, arrived 1 March 1943, departed 11 March 1943.\n\nAmerica came into the war with the bombing of [[Pearl Harbor]] by the Japanese in late 1941; the Allies began preparations for the invasion of Europe. RAF Chilbolton was then allocated to the Americans and transferred to the [[United States Army Air Forces]] (USAAF) playing host to Army Co-operation Command units.\n\n===USAAF use===\nChilbolton was known as '''USAAF Station AAF-404''' for security reasons by the USAAF during the war, and by which it was referred to instead of location.  Its RAF and USAAF Station Code was \"CB\".\n\n====368th Fighter Group====\nOn 1 March 1944 the 12th and 15th Tactical Reconnaissance Squadrons from the 67th Reconnaissance Wing, flying Spitfires and Mustangs, moved in from [[RAF Aldermaston]] to make way for a C-47 group, only to be ejected two weeks later when a new fighter group arrived.  The 368th had the following fighter squadrons and fuselage codes:\n* 395th Fighter Squadron (A7)\n* 396th Fighter Squadron (C2)\n* 397th Fighter Squadron (D3)\n\nThe 368th was a group of [[Ninth Air Force]]'s [[71st Fighter Wing (World War II)|71st Fighter Wing]], [[IX Tactical Air Command]].  \n \nChilbolton continued to be retained by the USAAF for use by transports as a staging airfield for cargo operations to and from the Continent and it was not returned to the RAF until March 1945 by which time most of the C-47 groups had been transferred to forward stations in France.\n\n===Back to RAF Control===\nIn the hands of the RAF, Chilbolton played host to a fighter Operational Training Unit - [[List of Royal Air Force Operational Training Units|No. 41 OTU]] - for the rest of [[World War II]], and then to several different fighter squadrons equipped with [[Supermarine Spitfire]]s and [[Hawker Tempest]]s as the RAF reduced its strength at the end of the war.\n* No 41 OTU, Hurricane/Spitfire/Master/Martinet arrived March 1945, disbanded 26 June 1945.\n* [[No. 26 Squadron RAF|26 Sqn]], Mustang I/Spitfire XIV, arrived 23 May 1945, departed 20 August 1945.\n* [[No. 183 Squadron RAF|183 Sqn]], Spitfire IX, arrived 17 June 1945, departed 8 October 1945.\n* [[No. 247 Squadron RAF|247 Sqn]], Tempest F2/Typhoon Ib, arrived 20 August 1945, departed 7 January 1946.\n* [[No. 222 Squadron RAF|222 Sqn]], Tempest V, arrived 10 August 1945, departed 15 August 1945.\n* [[No. 54 Squadron RAF|54 Sqn]], Tempest F2, arrived 15 November 1945, departed 28 June 1946.\n* 183 Sqn, Tempest II, arrived 15 November 1945, disbanded 15 November 1945.\n\n==== Into the 'Jet Age' ====\nIn March 1946, Chilbolton became the first RAF station to operate [[de Havilland Vampire]] jets when [[No. 247 Squadron RAF|247 squadron]] converted to Vampire FB1's, but by the late summer that year the station was on care and maintenance.\n* 247 Sqn, Tempest F2/Vampire F1, arrived 16 February 1946, departed 1 June 1946.\n* 247 Sqn, Vampire F1, arrived 12 June 1946, departed 27 June 1946.\n\n===Post war===\nWith the facility released from military control in 1946, [[Vickers|Vickers Supermarine]] selected the airfield as a location for conducting flight development programmes of their jet prototypes and development aircraft, remaining for the best part of ten years.  [[Supermarine Attacker]], [[Supermarine Swift]] and  [[Supermarine Scimitar]] were developed there as well as many early experimental swept wing jet fighters. The airfield was also used for some location filming of David Lean's classic film, [[The Sound Barrier]] in the early 1950s. The Spitfire T Mk IX, a 2-seat trainer and the last Spitfire variant to be built, was also developed and test flown at Chilbolton for export to India and Eire (Southern Ireland).\n\n[[Folland Aircraft]] also occupied another part of the airfield to conduct similar work on their products, chiefly the Midge and [[Folland Gnat|Gnat]], but were gone by the end of 1961.  With their departure, the wartime airfield began to be dismantled, with large sections of runway, perimeter track and loop hardstands being removed for hardcore.\n\nThe next organisation to take an active interest in the site was the Space Research Council which set about building an observatory with what was to become a prominent local landmark - a radio telescope, known as the [[Chilbolton Observatory]], which was built almost in the centre of the airfield, on the wartime main runway.  When constructed, the north end of the runway was removed, with a two lane access road replacing the runway and connecting to the local road network.   Various other enterprises flourished or faded in the buildings on the periphery of the airfield.\n\nFlying continued on the old airfield during the 1980s when helicopters and light aircraft serving a field spraying organisation were in residence using a grass strip built parallel to the main north\u2013south 12/30 runway.\n\n==Current use==\n\nToday, the perimeter track has been largely reduced to a single-lane farm road as much of the airfield has been returned to agricultural use.  A large section of the 06/24 secondary runway still exists, although reduced to half width.  In aerial photography, however, much of the former wartime airfield's runways and hardstands can be seen as disturbances on the landscape, giving a ghostly appearance to the area. A large Type B.1 hangar also survives in agricultural use on the Leckford Estate which occupies the SW corner of the former airfield.\n\nFlying still takes place at Chilbolton with the Chilbolton Flying Club having established an airstrip on the former playing fields in front of the old RAF gymnasium with planning consent being obtained in 1992. Today club members fly Light aircraft and Ultralights from the airstrip. see http://www.chilboltonflyingclub.co.uk/\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|World War II}}\n*[[List of former Royal Air Force stations]]\n\n==References==\n{{Air Force Historical Research Agency}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{commons category}}\n* Brooks, Robin. Hampshire Airfields in the Second World War. Countryside Books.\n* Freeman, Roger A. (1994) UK Airfields of the Ninth: Then and Now 1994. After the Battle {{ISBN|0-900913-80-0}}\n* Freeman, Roger A. (1996) The Ninth Air Force in Colour: UK and the Continent-World War Two. After the Battle {{ISBN|1-85409-272-3}}\n* Lockyer, Eleanor, M. English Airfields 1941-1945\n* Lockyer, Eleanor, M. English Airfields 1945-1962\n* Lockyer, Eleanor, M. Chilbolton Memories 1941-45\n* Maurer, Maurer (1983) Air Force Combat Units Of World War II. Maxwell AFB, Alabama: Office of Air Force History. {{ISBN|0-89201-092-4}}.\n* [http://home.att.net/~jbaugher/usafserials.html USAAS-USAAC-USAAF-USAF Aircraft Serial Numbers--1908 to present]\n\n{{Royal Air Force}}\n{{USAAF 9th Air Force UK}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chilbolton}}\n[[Category:Airfields of the IX Fighter Command in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Airfields of the IX Troop Carrier Command in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:History of Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Royal Air Force stations in Hampshire]]\n[[Category:Military airbases established in 1940]]\n[[Category:Military installations closed in 1946]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox airport \n| name = RAF Chilbolton<br>USAAF Station AAF-404\n| nativename =  [[File:Ensign of the Royal Air Force.svg|90px]][[File:Patch9thusaaf.png|60px]]\n| nativename-a = \n| nativename-r = \n| image = Chilbolton-20apr44.jpg\n| image-width = 250px\n| caption = Aerial Photo of Chilbolton Airfield - 20 April 1944   \n| IATA = \n| ICAO = \n| type = Military   \n| owner = [[Air Ministry]]   \n| operator = [[Royal Air Force]]<br>[[United States Army Air Forces]]\n| city-served = \n| location = [[Chilbolton]], [[Hampshire]]\n| built = {{Start date|1938}}\n| used = 1940-{{End date|1946}}\n| elevation-f = {{Convert|84|m|disp=output number only|0}}\n| elevation-m = 84\n| coordinates = {{coord|51|08|36|N|001|26|23|W|region:GB_type:airport|display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_map = Hampshire\n| pushpin_label = RAF Chilbolton\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location in Hampshire\n| website = \n| r1-number = 02/20\n| r1-length-f = 4,800\n| r1-length-m = 0\n| r1-surface = [[Asphalt]]   \n| r2-number = 06/24\n| r2-length-f = 4,200\n| r2-length-m = 0\n| r2-surface = Asphalt \n| r3-number = 12/30\n| r3-length-f = 5,400\n| r3-length-m = 0\n| r3-surface = Asphalt \n| stat-year = \n| stat1-header = \n| stat1-data = \n| stat2-header = \n| stat2-data = \n}}\n[[File:Chil-p47-368fg.jpg|thumb|Republic P-47D-30-RE Thunderbolt Serial 44-20456 of the 397th Fighter Squadron on an escort mission over the German Alps.]]\n[[File:Chil-442tcg-1.jpg|thumb|Chilbolton loaded with CG-4As and C-47s to use in Operation \"Market\", September 1944.]]\n[[File:Chil-cg4a-442tcg.jpg|thumb|Closeup of CG-4As marshalled at Chilbolton in early September 1944 ready to be used in Operation \"Market\". Many of these gliders had been used in the 6 June D-Day invasion.]]\n\n'''Royal Air Force Station Chilbolton''' or '''RAF Chilbolton''' is a former [[Royal Air Force]] [[Royal Air Force station|station]] in [[Hampshire]], [[England]].  The airfield is located in [[Chilbolton]] approximately {{convert|4|mi|km}} south-southeast of [[Andover, Hampshire|Andover]]; about {{convert|62|mi|km}} southwest of [[London]]\n\nOpened in 1940, it was used by both the [[Royal Air Force]] and then later by the [[United States Army Air Forces]].  During the war it was used primarily as a troop carrier airfield for parachutists.  After the war it was used for military jet aircraft training before closing as an RAF station in 1946, although it was then used until the early 1960s by the Vickers-Supermarine and Folland aircraft companies for flight testing and development flying. \n\nToday the remains of the airfield are located on private property being used as agricultural fields.\n\n==History==\n\n===Royal Air Force use===\nRAF Chilbolton was opened in September 1940 as a satellite of [[RAF Middle Wallop]] and was used as a relief landing ground by the [[Royal Air Force]] (RAF).  At first it was developed piecemeal with the addition of the necessary facilities that took it towards existence as an independent airfield.  It then hosted its own [[Hawker Hurricane]] squadrons which took part in the [[Battle of Britain]].  [[No. 238 Squadron RAF]] operated throughout the Battle of Britain from Middle Wallop and [[RAF St Eval]] as part of [[No. 10 Group RAF|No. 10 Group]] Fighter Command, posted to Chilbolton in September 1940 with Hurricane Is.\n\nDuring the Battle of Britain many sorties were flown covering [[Southampton]] to [[Bristol]].\nOnce the battle had been won and therefore the threat of invasion had passed major [[Luftwaffe]] raids ceased.  Several [[Supermarine Spitfire]] and Hurricane squadrons came and went, none stayed very long.\n\nBy late 1941 Chilbolton had been upgraded with the addition of a perimeter track and several fighter concrete dispersal pens around it.\n\nBy November 1941 it was placed into Care and Maintenance as there was no use for it by then as the Battle of Britain had ended and there were sufficient airfields in the area to continue the war without it.\n\nRAF Units stationed at Chilbolton:\n* [[No. 238 Squadron RAF|238 Sqn]], Hurricane I, arrived 30 September 1940, departed 20 May 1941.\n* Glider Pilots Exercise Unit, [[de Havilland Tiger Moth]]/[[Miles Master]]/[[General Aircraft Hotspur]] arrived Dec-Jan 1941.\n* 238 Sqn, Hurricane IIA, arrived 1 February 1941, departed April 1941.\n* [[No. 308 Squadron RAF|308 Sqn]], Spitfire IIA, arrived 31 May 1941, departed 24 June 1941.\n* [[No. 501 Squadron RAF|501 Sqn]], Spitfire IIA, arrived 25 June 1941, departed 5 August 1941.\n* [[No. 504 Squadron RAF|504 Sqn]], Hurricane IIB, arrived 11 August 1941, departed 26 August 1941.\n* [[No. 245 Squadron RAF|245 Sqn]], Hurricane IIB, arrived 1 September 1941, departed 17 Nov 1941.\n* 245 Sqn, Hurricane IIB, arrived 23 Nov 1941, departed 19 Dec 1941.\n* [[No. 184 Squadron RAF|184 Sqn]], Hurricane IID, arrived 1 March 1943, departed 11 March 1943.\n* [[No. 174 Squadron RAF|174 Sqn]], Hurricane IIB, arrived 1 March 1943, departed 11 March 1943.\n\nAmerica came into the war with the bombing of [[Pearl Harbor]] by the Japanese in late 1941; the Allies began preparations for the invasion of Europe. RAF Chilbolton was then allocated to the Americans and transferred to the [[United States Army Air Forces]] (USAAF) playing host to Army Co-operation Command units.\n\n===USAAF use===\nChilbolton was known as '''USAAF Station AAF-404''' for security reasons by the USAAF during the war, and by which it was referred to instead of location.  Its RAF and USAAF Station Code was \"CB\".\n\n====368th Fighter Group====\nOn 1 March 1944 the 12th and 15th Tactical Reconnaissance Squadrons from the 67th Reconnaissance Wing, flying Spitfires and Mustangs, moved in from [[RAF Aldermaston]] to make way for a C-47 group, only to be ejected two weeks later when a new fighter group arrived.  The 368th had the following fighter squadrons and fuselage codes:\n* 395th Fighter Squadron (A7)\n* 396th Fighter Squadron (C2)\n* 397th Fighter Squadron (D3)\n\nThe 368th was a group of [[Ninth Air Force]]'s [[71st Fighter Wing (World War II)|71st Fighter Wing]], [[IX Tactical Air Command]].  \n \nChilbolton continued to be retained by the USAAF for use by transports as a staging airfield for cargo operations to and from the Continent and it was not returned to the RAF until March 1945 by which time most of the C-47 groups had been transferred to forward stations in France.\n\n===Back to RAF Control===\nIn the hands of the RAF, Chilbolton played host to a fighter Operational Training Unit - [[List of Royal Air Force Operational Training Units|No. 41 OTU]] - for the rest of [[World War II]], and then to several different fighter squadrons equipped with [[Supermarine Spitfire]]s and [[Hawker Tempest]]s as the RAF reduced its strength at the end of the war.\n* No 41 OTU, Hurricane/Spitfire/Master/Martinet arrived March 1945, disbanded 26 June 1945.\n* [[No. 26 Squadron RAF|26 Sqn]], Mustang I/Spitfire XIV, arrived 23 May 1945, departed 20 August 1945.\n* [[No. 183 Squadron RAF|183 Sqn]], Spitfire IX, arrived 17 June 1945, departed 8 October 1945.\n* [[No. 247 Squadron RAF|247 Sqn]], Tempest F2/Typhoon Ib, arrived 20 August 1945, departed 7 January 1946.\n* [[No. 222 Squadron RAF|222 Sqn]], Tempest V, arrived 10 August 1945, departed 15 August 1945.\n* [[No. 54 Squadron RAF|54 Sqn]], Tempest F2, arrived 15 November 1945, departed 28 June 1946.\n* 183 Sqn, Tempest II, arrived 15 November 1945, disbanded 15 November 1945.\n\n==== Into the 'Jet Age' ====\nIn March 1946, Chilbolton became the first RAF station to operate [[de Havilland Vampire]] jets when [[No. 247 Squadron RAF|247 squadron]] converted to Vampire FB1's, but by the late summer that year the station was on care and maintenance.\n* 247 Sqn, Tempest F2/Vampire F1, arrived 16 February 1946, departed 1 June 1946.\n* 247 Sqn, Vampire F1, arrived 12 June 1946, departed 27 June 1946.\n\n===Post war===\nWith the facility released from military control in 1946, [[Vickers|Vickers Supermarine]] selected the airfield as a location for conducting flight development programmes of their jet prototypes and development aircraft, remaining for the best part of ten years.  [[Supermarine Attacker]], [[Supermarine Swift]] and  [[Supermarine Scimitar]] were developed there as well as many early experimental swept wing jet fighters. The airfield was also used for some location filming of David Lean's classic film, [[The Sound Barrier]] in the early 1950s. The Spitfire T Mk IX, a 2-seat trainer and the last Spitfire variant to be built, was also developed and test flown at Chilbolton for export to India and Eire (Southern Ireland).\n\n[[Folland Aircraft]] also occupied another part of the airfield to conduct similar work on their products, chiefly the Midge and [[Folland Gnat|Gnat]], but were gone by the end of 1961.  With their departure, the wartime airfield began to be dismantled, with large sections of runway, perimeter track and loop hardstands being removed for hardcore.\n\nThe next organisation to take an active interest in the site was the Space Research Council which set about building an observatory with what was to become a prominent local landmark - a radio telescope, known as the [[Chilbolton Observatory]], which was built almost in the centre of the airfield, on the wartime main runway.  When constructed, the north end of the runway was removed, with a two lane access road replacing the runway and connecting to the local road network.   Various other enterprises flourished or faded in the buildings on the periphery of the airfield.\n\nFlying continued on the old airfield during the 1980s when helicopters and light aircraft serving a field spraying organisation were in residence using a grass strip built parallel to the main north-south 12/30 runway.\n\n==Current use==\n\nToday, the perimeter track has been largely reduced to a single-lane farm road as much of the airfield has been returned to agricultural use.  A large section of the 06/24 secondary runway still exists, although reduced to half width.  In aerial photography, however, much of the former wartime airfield's runways and hardstands can be seen as disturbances on the landscape, giving a ghostly appearance to the area. A large Type B.1 hangar also survives in agricultural use on the Leckford Estate which occupies the SW corner of the former airfield.\n\nFlying still takes place at Chilbolton with the Chilbolton Flying Club having established an airstrip on the former playing fields in front of the old RAF gymnasium with planning consent being obtained in 1992. Today club members fly Light aircraft and Ultralights from the airstrip. see http://www.chilboltonflyingclub.co.uk/\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|World War II}}\n*[[List of former Royal Air Force stations]]\n\n==References==\n{{Air Force Historical Research Agency}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{commons category}}\n* Brooks, Robin. Hampshire Airfields in the Second World War. Countryside Books.\n* Freeman, Roger A. (1994) UK Airfields of the Ninth: Then and Now 1994. After the Battle {{ISBN|0-900913-80-0}}\n* Freeman, Roger A. (1996) The Ninth Air Force in Colour: UK and the Continent-World War Two. After the Battle {{ISBN|1-85409-272-3}}\n* Lockyer, Eleanor, M. English Airfields 1941-1945\n* Lockyer, Eleanor, M. English Airfields 1945-1962\n* Lockyer, Eleanor, M. Chilbolton Memories 1941-45\n* Maurer, Maurer (1983) Air Force Combat Units Of World War II. Maxwell AFB, Alabama: Office of Air Force History. {{ISBN|0-89201-092-4}}.\n* [http://home.att.net/~jbaugher/usafserials.html USAAS-USAAC-USAAF-USAF Aircraft Serial Numbers--1908 to present]\n\n{{Royal Air Force}}\n{{USAAF